<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK, Japan Willing to Establish Good-neighborly, Friendly Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) and Japan expressed their willingness here
Wednesday to normalize their diplomatic ties and establish good-
neighborly and friendly relationship.
</P>
<P>
During the first ever meeting between the foreign ministers of
the two countries in 52 years, DPRK Foreign Minister Paek Nam Sun
said DPRK wants to normalize the bilateral relations with Japan as
soon as possible and establish good-neighborly and friendly ties
based on the principles of respect of sovereignty, equality,
mutual benefit and non-interference, according to the Japanese
foreign ministry spokesman here.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing after the historic meeting between the two
foreign ministers, which lasted more than two hours, the spokesman
said that both sides hoped that the meeting will bring about
positive effects on the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Paek was quoted as saying that it is important to settle the
past issues between DPRK and Japan and is necessary to promote
bilateral exchanges and cooperation for normalizing the relations.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK foreign minister said the improvement of the bilateral
ties is not only important for peace and stability in northeast
Asia but also for Asia as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Yohei Kono agreed that "Japan and
DPRK should build confidence and hold frank talks to normalize
diplomatic relationship."
</P>
<P>
"It's important to improve the atmosphere with understanding of
mutual concerns and national emotions," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers signed a four-point joint statement during
their meeting aimed at improving the relations between the two
countries, including holding of the 10th round talks for
normalization in Tokyo from August 21 to 25.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers are here to attend the 7th ASEAN
Regional Forum (ARF) scheduled on Thursday for discussions of
political and security issues. It is the first time for DPRK to
participate in ARF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Foreign Minister Refutes Indian Embassy's Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Foreign Minister Chakra
Prasad Bastola said here Wednesday that the communique issued by
the Indian embassy Tuesday concerning the Laxmanpur Dam has left
the Nepali government dismayed.
</P>
<P>
Talking to RSS, the official Nepali news agency, Bastola said
he wondered why such a statement has come from the Indian
government on the eve of Nepali prime minister's visit to India.
</P>
<P>
"The matter is a serious one," Bastola said.
</P>
<P>
"The embankment is not constructed after consulting Nepal and
Nepal's territory has been inundated," he continued. "It is Nepal
that is in a difficulty, but India insists Nepal has not been
affected in any way. Nepal is not prepared to accept that."
</P>
<P>
The communique by the Indian embassy claimed that India did not
violate any international laws by building the Laxmanpur Dam and
that the main barrage structure along with the guide bunds "has
not resulted in, and is not likely to result in, any inundation or
submergence of villages on the Nepalese side."
</P>
<P>
The communique is in response to a Nepali parliament human
rights committee that said the construction of the dam and the
adjoining afflux bund was an unilateral decision of the Indian
government and a violation of the international law.
</P>
<P>
The committee claimed that the dam is likely to inundate around
33 villages, displacing 1,500 people and affecting thousands of
others in southern Banke district in the mid-western Terai plain
that borders India.
</P>
<P>
According to Nepali officials, the 13.6 km long Laxmanpur Dam
lies at a distance of 4.25 km from the Nepal-India border on the
Indian side. But the communique by the Indian embassy said the
distance is 8 km in line with the requirement of international
practice.
</P>
<P>
Bastola said the dam dispute is to be resolved through
discussions between the two countries and at a technical level.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that Nepal will not enter into any agreement
that will compromise Nepal's national interest.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Prime Minister Girija Koirala is scheduled to pay a one-
week official visit to India from July 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
