<HEADLINE> Xinhua Middle East News Summary at 2000 GMT, Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA -- Palestinian and Israeli officials Wednesday evening held
a meeting here to discuss boosting security cooperation in order to
head off violence in view of the collapse of the Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Secretary General Tayeb Abdul Rahim and Minister of
Civil Affairs Jamil Tarifi and Israeli Deputy Defense Minister and
Palestinian territory coordinator Jacob Ar attended the meeting,
according to Palestinian sources. (Palestine-Israel-Security)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq's first computer center was opened here on
Thursday, which would allow ordinary Iraqis to surf the Internet
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Transport and Communications Ahmad Murtadha
Ahmad Khalil cut the ribbon at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has lagged far behind in information technology, with
people having had no access to the Internet, mainly due to the
sweeping sanctions imposed by the United Nations in 1990 after its
invasion of neighboring Kuwait. (Iraq-Internet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- It is impossible to reach an Israeli-Palestinian
agreement without painful Israeli compromise on the Jerusalem
issue, Israel's left-wing Meretz party said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The secular Meretz maintained that any solution to the issue
should be based on "joint sovereignty," in which Israel controls
Jewish neighborhoods and the Palestinians control Arab villages in
East Jerusalem, party officials said. (Israel-Palestine-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiators will resume
peace talks on Sunday to move the Israeli-Palestinian track
forward.
</P>
<P>
Israeli negotiator Gilead Sher and chief Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat said separately on Thursday that they hoped an
agreement could be reached soon, despite the collapse of the
summit.
</P>
<P>
"I would say that definitely yes, it is possible to finish the
conflict and reach a reasonable agreement in not too long a time so
long as there is talk between the sides," Sher told the Israel
Radio. (Israel-Palestinians-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The leadership of Israel's ultra-Orthodox Shas
party Thursday expressed willingness to return to the coalition
government provided that the party be equally treated.
</P>
<P>
Shas's decision-making body, the Council of Torah Sages, met
Thursday to discuss the party's current status as an opposition
party.
</P>
<P>
Shas's Knesset (Parliament) member Yitzhak Vaknin told reporters
that the party's spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef is more
concerned about protecting human life than symbols important to the
Jewish people. (Israel-Coalition-Shas) 
</P>
</TEXT>
