<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Trial Into Summer Recess With Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, the Netherlands, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Lawyers at the
Lockerbie trial reached agreement Thursday when the trial went
into summer recess.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said in a statement issued late Thursday that they
now expect to complete their case by the end of September. The
long-awaited trial, which went underway on May 3 after almost 12
years of investigation and preparation, had been expected to last
at least a year.
</P>
<P>
The proceedings of the trial will be shortened as the
prosecution and the defense team reached agreement on a number of
evidence.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor Alan Turnbull told the court that 60 relatives and
friends of the Lockerbie bombing victims would no longer testify
at the Scottish court on Dutch soil.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers had already agreed to shorten the list of witnesses
so as to shorten the trial shortly after the trial had started.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors charge Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-Amin Khalifa
Fahima with conspiracy of murder and breach of international
aircraft safety laws. They say that the two Libyans accused,
posing as Libyan Arab Airlines employees at the Luqa airport in
Malta, have put a bomb on a plane bound for Frankfurt where the
bomb was transferred onto Pan Am Flight 103 that was exploded mid-
air over the Scottish town of Lockerbie on December 21, 1988,
killing 259 people on board and 11 others on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyers argue that the bomb was placed in the New York-
bound airliner by Palestinian guerrillas in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The trial is now set to resume on August 22 when the
prosecution is expected to bring witnesses to provide evidence
about events that happened at the Luqa, Frankfurt and Heathrow
airports.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution, according to the Scots law, has to prove its
case beyond reasonable doubt for the three Scottish judges to give
their verdict.
</P>
<P>
If proved guilty, the two Libyans would have to serve their
life sentence in Scotland; if the prosecution could not establish
its case, the two would have to be set free. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Castro Demands Total U.S. Blockade Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, JULY 27 (Xinhua)) -- Cuban President Fidel Castro has
demanded a total lifting of the United States' blockade against
his country.
</P>
<P>
Castro, in statements published Thursday by the press, said
that an eventual end to U.S. sales of medicines and food to Cuba
means making flexible the nearly 40-year embargo against the
island.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban leader pronounced his statements at Conventions
Palace after he was awarded International Prize Benito Juarez (
Mexican leader) for his defense of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Cuban authorities have viewed with reserve the approval by the
U.S. House of Representatives to lift the medicine and food
embargo against the island as a prelude to the economic one.
</P>
<P>
The daily "Granma," organ of the Cuban Communist Party, said
Tuesday in an editorial that the blockade has caused Cuba damages
that go over 100 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Castro assured the island won't stop half-way and will reach
the end of the political battle against the U.S. anti-Cuban
rulings such as the Cuban Adjustment Act, Torricelli and Helms-
Burton Law.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives last week voted to stop
enforcing provisions that ban American food exports and limit
sales of U.S. medicine to Cuba and four other nations -- Iran,
Libya, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea and Sudan. The U.
S. Senate passed a bill on the same day to permit food and medical
sales to the five countries
</P>
<P>
While Cuba welcomed the moves, it said they do not go far
enough and continued to demand a total lifting of the sanctions
</P>
<P>
Cuba has been under a total trade embargo since February 1962,
longer than any other country except the DPRK. The sanctions were
tightened in July 1963, and most travels by Americans to the
island then were made illegal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
