<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Earns Another 296 Million Dollars in U.N. Oil-for-Oil Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraq earned some 296
million U.S. dollars last week from exporting over 13 million
barrels of oil, the U.N. reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Office of the Iraq Program, which
administers the U.N. humanitarian oil-for-food program, said that
since the program's current six-month period, known as "phase VIII,
" began on June 9, Iraq has earned an estimated 1.732 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the United Nations Security Council's sanctions
monitoring panel approved 12 new contracts for the sale of Iraqi
oil under phase VIII, bringing the total of approved contracts
within the phase to 80 with a volume of nearly 344.4 million
barrels, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Overall, since the program began in December 1996, Iraq has
exported more than 1.904 billion barrels of oil valued at more
than 30.7 billion dollars, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, humanitarian supplies and equipment for the oil
industry continued to arrive normally last week, it added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990. The oil-for-food program began to implement in
late 1996, which was aimed to ease the deteriorating humanitarian
situation in the country caused by the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions cannon be lifted until Iraq has destroyed all
its weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
