<HEADLINE> Britain Says Angola's Rebel Still Violating Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Thursday that
Angola's UNITA rebels were still violating United Nations
sanctions by selling diamonds to fund their war effort.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Office minister Peter Hain said in a written statement
to the parliament that sales of UNITA diamonds had been taking
place in the Gabonese capital Libreville.
</P>
<P>
"We have heard that another private sale may be held in
Libreville within the next month," Hain added.
</P>
<P>
"We will be raising these reports urgently with the Gabonese
authorities, and urging them to do everything in their power to
prevent this illicit trade," he said.
</P>
<P>
Britain has repeatedly campaigned for measures to combat the
trade in "conflict diamonds" which fuel some of Africa's most
bloody wars.
</P>
<P>
Hain said Britain would pass information about the sales to the
U.N. Angola sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed an arms and fuel ban on UNITA
in an effort to end a civil war in the former Portuguese colony
that has killed at least one million people.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 it added an embargo on the rebel diamond trade.
</P>
