<HEADLINE> Arafat to Hold Arab, International Contacts Soon: PNA Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
Chairman Yasser Arafat will hold a series of contacts with Arab,
European and other countries over the coming days to assess the
Middle East peace process after the failure of the Camp David
summit.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Arafat's adviser Nabil Abu Rudainah
in an interview with Voice of Arabs radio on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab support is essential and very important for the
Palestinian negotiators," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He held Israel responsible for the failure of the Camp David
summit, which was held on July 11-25 at the U.S. presidential
retreat near Washington, and accused Israel of attempting to "
retain its occupation of Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
"Arafat's position was very clear and meant that there would be
neither peace nor reconciliation without the return of Jerusalem
and the Islamic and Christian holy sites to full Palestinian
control," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Jerusalem was the basis and axis of the talks with Israel," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat told U.S. President Bill Clinton and Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak during the talks that the Holy City was a "red
line" and that it was "not only a Palestinian issue but also an
Arab, Islamic and Christian one."
</P>
<P>
"No one can yield an inch of Jerusalem," Rudainah quoted Arafat
as saying to the U.S. and Israeli leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side is calling for holding an all-round or a
small Arab summit to discuss the issue of Jerusalem, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are for Arab coordination and solidarity as we are on the
threshold of a fateful stage in the peace process," the PNA
official added.
</P>
<P>
He further blamed the Israeli side for evading its commitments
to the principles of the peace process, including the references of
the 1993 Madrid peace conference and the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
He underscored the necessity to find a fair and satisfactory
solution to the question of Palestinian refugees, as well as other
final-status issues.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he urged the United States to continue its support
for Arafat, adding "We seek an effective U.S. role to force Israel
to comply with the principles of the peace process."
</P>
<P>
As for the Palestinian statehood, he said that the Central
Council of the Palestine Liberation Organization (PCC) would decide
on it in the coming session.
</P>
<P>
"The decision will be an independent Arab Palestinian one," he
noted, adding that "Arafat asserted repeatedly that 2,000 would be
the year of the declaration of the Palestinian state with Jerusalem
as its capital."
</P>
<P>
Early July the PCC said the Palestinian independent state would
be declared on September 13 as the interim stage of the peace talks
would come to an end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
