<HEADLINE> Palestinian Minister Briefs Jordan on Camp David Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 27 (Xinhua ) -- Palestinian Minister of Culture and
Information Yasser Abed Rabou paid a brief visit to Jordan on
Thursday to brief the kingdom on the outcome of a two-week
trilateral summit between U.S., Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel Ilah al-
Khatib, Rabou conveyed a message to King Abdullah Bin Hussein from
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on the outcomes of the U.S.-
sponsored Palestinian-Israeli negotiations at Camp David near
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Rabou told Khatib that the peace process on the Palestinian-
Israeli track will continue, and the Palestinians valued and
appreciated Jordan's support for their negotiators during the final
status talks with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
He also said Arafat is keen to continue coordination with King
Abdullah over the peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
Rabou is the first senior Palestinian official to visit Jordan
after the Camp David summit ended earlier this week without any
agreement on the future of Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees, borders
and security arrangements between Israel and a future Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
The marathon summit, held on July 11-25, was attended by U.S.
President Bill Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel and the Palestinians have agreed to resume their
final status talks at lower levels by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The talks are closely followed by Jordan, which said it has its
own interests to be protected, particularly on the issue of
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom is currently hosting some 1.5 million Palestinian
refugees displaced during successive Arab-Israeli wars since the
creation of Israel in 1948.
</P>
<P>
Most of the refugees have been granted Jordanian citizenship,
but the government said it did not mean they have given up their
rights to return home or stay in Jordan while being compensated in
accordance with relevant U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
