<HEADLINE> Egypt Renews Detention of Social Activist for 15 More Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's Higher State Security
Prosecution on Thursday renewed detention of Saad Eddin Ibrahim, a
social developments activist, for 15 more days pending
investigations.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim, director of the Ibn Khaldoun Center for Social
Developments, was arrested on June 30 on charges of collaborating
with foreign parties to undermine Egypt's social stability and the
center has also been closed temporarily, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He was also accused of receiving funds from foreign sources,
including the European Union, without prior permission of the
Egyptian authorities, for preparing reports and producing films,
which the authorities said tarnished Egypt's image.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim continues to be held in Torah prison outside Cairo
without trial. He could be sentenced to 15 years in jail if found
guilty.
</P>
<P>
Under Egypt's emergency laws, those suspected of threatening
state security can be detained without formal charges for 15 days,
a period which can be renewed indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
The security prosecution also renewed detention for another 15
days of the center's Sudanese accountant Nadia Abdel Nur, who was
arrested at the same time as Ibrahim and being investigated in the
case, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Twelve other people from the center and the Woman Voters'
Support Center also have been detained in connection to the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
