<HEADLINE> Mediators Optimistic on Burundi Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Mediators said here Thursday
that they remained optimistic about the signing of a peace
agreement on August 28 despite the rejection by a main rebel group.
</P>
<P>
They vowed to push for an end to the seven-year conflict in the
tiny central African country, saying everything was still on
course for the signing of the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
"The scheduled signing of the draft peace agreement will go on
as planned," the leader of the Burundi peace talks mediation team
Judge Marke Bomani said, adding that the agreement was an all-
inclusive, comprehensive document.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Burundi's key Hutu rebel group, the National
Council for the Defense of Democracy Forces for the Defense of
Democracy (CNDD-FDD), rejected the draft agreement as a "violation
of the 1992 Burundi constitution".
</P>
<P>
CNDD-FDD joined for the first time 19 Burundian political
parties in the peace talks in northern Tanzanian town of Arusha
last week.
</P>
<P>
Though no agreement was reached, the facilitator, former South
African president Nelson Mandela set August 28 as a new deadline
for signing.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of Tanzanian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and
International Cooperation said that peace remained elusive in
Burundi despite some progress was made in the latest round of
talks.
</P>
<P>
They added that the signing of a peace agreement may have to be
postponed once again because several key issues are yet to be
resolved.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the mediation team said that the question of
who will lead the transitional government in Burundi is the most
intractable issue facing the negotiators.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi conflict between Hutu rebels and minority Tutsi
dominated government and army has claimed 200,000 lives since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Burundi President Pierre Buyoya recently warned of a premature
signing of a peace agreement, saying a cease-fire must come into
effect before any accord is signed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
