<HEADLINE> 2 Engines Could Have Failed in Concorde Crash: Investigators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bureau of Investigation of Accident (BEA) said in its first
communique since the accident took place that the crew of the
plane also told the control tower that the undercarriage of the
plane could not retract.
</P>
<P>
Investigators have found the remains of tires near the runway
of the airport, indicating that a tire broke out when the plane
took off.
</P>
<P>
While it is certain that the number two engine which is nearest
the fuselage broke down, the other engine on the wing -- number
one engine -- could also have broken down just before the plane
crashed, said the BEA.
</P>
<P>
"During the take-off, while the plane surpassed V1 (speed of
decision), the control tower signaled to the crew the fire in the
back part of the plane. We noted in the phone recorder (black box)
that after the rotating movement, the crew announced a failure of
the number two engine and a little bit later that the
undercarriage did not retract," said the BEA.
</P>
<P>
The black box registering technical data showed that the power
of number two engine broke down until it stopped completely and
that of number one engine also broke down twice in less than one
minute just before the plane inclined to the left and crashed.
</P>
<P>
The failure of both engines explained the loss of balance of
the plane during its turning.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the fire of number two could have spread to
the number one engine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
