<HEADLINE> Russia, Kyrgyzstan Sign Friendship Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of Russia and
Kyrgyzstan signed here Thursday a declaration on friendship,
cooperation and partnership between the two former Soviet
republics.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Vladimir Putin and Kyrgyz President Askar
Akayev also signed a treaty of economic cooperation for 2000-2009,
the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Putin emphasized that the
Russian administration has a high regard for the level of
relations between the two countries and the prospects for their
development.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides "have similar or close views on many key
issues of international relations" and that this similarity is to
a great extent based on the fundamental principles of
international communication.
</P>
<P>
However, Putin said, the relations between Russia and
Kyrgyzstan "have a special nature" as Kyrgyzstan is "the most
active participant in the integration processes in the CIS (
Commonwealth of Independent States)."
</P>
<P>
Akayev, who arrived here Wednesday on an official visit, will
meet with chiefs of the Russian defense and security agencies to
discuss security in Central Asia Friday, Interfax said, noting
that Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev will brief Akayev on the
potential for supplying Russian defense hardware to Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
After his talks with Putin Thursday, Akayev said his summit
with Putin confirmed the two countries' strategic partnership and
Russia's new foreign policy respect for the independence of
Kyrgyzstan and other newly formed countries.
</P>
<P>
He said there is absolutely no reason to speak of any Russian
expansion against the newly independent states.
</P>
<P>
"Russia has always been a guarantor of stability in Central
Asia and the world," Akayev said. 
</P>
