<P>
The Security Council called on the parties concerned to respect
the withdrawal line, to exercise utmost restraint and to cooperate
fully with the United Nations and the UNIFIL established in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The council also called upon the Lebanese government to ensure
the return of its effective authority and presence in the south,
and in particular to proceed with a significant deployment of the
Lebanese armed forces as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The council welcomed the establishment by the Lebanese
government of checkpoints in the vacated area and encouraged it to
ensure a calm environment throughout the south, including through
the control of all checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
The council said it would review the situation by early
November and consider any steps it deems appropriate regarding the
UNIFIL on the basis of a report to be submitted by the U.N. chief
on October 31.
</P>
<P>
This is the first renewal of the mandate of the UNIFIL since
Israel announced the complete withdrawal of its troops from
southern Lebanon on May 24.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council endorsed earlier this week to deploy the
UNIFIL in southern Lebanon. But there is still one remaining
border violation by Israel in the process of being rectified.
</P>
<P>
The UNIFIL and Lebanese troops are not ready to deploy in
southern Lebanon until all Israeli violations of the border are
cleared up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
