<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Minister Sees 5.5 Percent Growth in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia's gross domestic product
could rise by 5.5 percent this year if the current positive trend
continues, Economic Development and Trade Minister German Gref
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary data, during the first half of the
year, GDP grew by 7.3 percent as compared with that of the
previous year, the Interfax news agency quoted Gref as saying.
</P>
<P>
The final figures will not be known until September when the
State Statistics Committee publishes the official results for the
first six months.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production continued to grow strongly in the six
months, rising 9.8 percent in June and 10.6 percent in May, Gref
said.
</P>
<P>
Capital investment rose more rapidly in the first half,
increasing by 14.3 percent year on year, including by 15.4 percent
in June alone, he said.
</P>
<P>
Gref predicted that the country's industrial output would rise
by about 7.5 percent for the whole 2000, some way above the 6
percent forecasted earlier.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Russians' real income will go up by some 6.5
percent in 2000 rather than by 6 percent as expected earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
