<HEADLINE> IMF Approves 13.2 Million Dollars In Credit to Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) approved Thursday the disbursement of 13.2 million U.S.
dollars to Zambia to help the east African nation combat poverty
and complete the privatization of its economy.
</P>
<P>
The funds, part of an overall three-year IMF Poverty Reduction
and Growth Facility credit for Zambia worth 336.3 million dollars,
followed a review by the fund of the country's recent economic
performance. Zambia to date has drawn about 26.4 million dollars
of the credit.
</P>
<P>
"The authorities' firm commitment to poverty reduction, as
outlined in their Interim Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper, is
welcome," IMF Deputy Managing Director Shigemitsu Sugisaki said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
He cited in particular the government's willingness to "
establish a legal framework that sustains private sector-led
economic growth, promotes stable macroeconomic conditions
conducive to private investment and targets poverty reduction
programs."
</P>
<P>
But he cautioned that the success of the effort depends on the
government's commitment to budget discipline ahead of elections
next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
