<HEADLINE> Jordan's Interests Must be Protected in Final Status Talks: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel Ilah
al-Khatib stressed on Thursday that Jordan's interests must be
safeguarded in the ongoing final status talks between Israel and
the Palestinians, particularly on the issue of Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Khatib said Jordan has been playing a
pivotal role in the Middle East peace process due to the
significance of its outcomes on the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
"All parties concerned in the process are well-aware of the
Jordanian stance regarding the country's interests, and Jordan has
extensively and meticulously acquainted them of its stand in regard
to the issue of (Palestinian)refugees," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is sheltering some 1.5 million Palestinian refugees who
had
fled their homes in successive wars in the region since the
creation of Israel in 1948.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government said the refugees should return home
under relevant U.N. resolutions or stay in Jordan while asking for
compensations from all parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
Khatib said most of the refugees have been granted Jordanian
citizenship, but it does not mean they have given up their rights
to return home or be compensated.
</P>
<P>
He also called on Arab nations to join hands with Jordan in
supporting an independent Palestinian state upon their own soil.
</P>
<P>
He announced that King Abdullah Bin Hussein will visit Egypt
next
Monday for talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on the peace
process after a two-week-long trilateral summit at Camp David near
Washington failed to reach any agreement.
</P>
<P>
The summit meetings, attended by U.S. President Bill Clinton,
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, mainly focused on thorny issues such as the status of
Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees, borders of a future Palestinian
state and security arrangements between Israel and the future
Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
Khatib denied Jordan was excluded from the Camp David summit,
saying "the kingdom has supported the peace process and will do so
to help restore Palestinian legitimate rights and to achieve a just
and comprehensive peace in the region."
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that negotiations between Palestinians and
Israelis will build on what has been achieved at Camp David to make
real and tangible progress and then to pave the way for signing an
agreement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"Jordanian stand in supporting Palestinians and the peace
process is crystal clear and needs nobody's testimony. It stems
from our commitment to the peace process and our support to Arab
brothers," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
