<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Shas Party Signals Willingness to Rejoin Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The leadership of Israel's ultra-
Orthodox Shas party Thursday expressed willingness to return to the
coalition government provided that the party be equally treated.
</P>
<P>
Shas's decision-making body, the Council of Torah Sages, met
Thursday to discuss the party's current status as an opposition
party.
</P>
<P>
Shas's Knesset (Parliament) member Yitzhak Vaknin told reporters
that the party's spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef is more
concerned about protecting human life than symbols important to the
Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
In Rabbi Yosef's opinion, Vaknin said, a peace deal that
protects human life takes precedence over things that are only of
symbolic value. As long as it is possible to save a Jewish life,
everything possible must be done.
</P>
<P>
Shas will return to the coalition as a partner in the peace
process if the party is treated as equal, the party's mentor said.
</P>
<P>
Shas, the third largest party in Israel with 17 seats in the
120-member Knesset, bolted the coalition on the eve of Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's departure for the Camp David summit to shirk
the responsibility for a possible bad deal that Barak might bring
back from the summit.
</P>
<P>
Three weeks earlier, Shas, the largest ruling partner in Barak's
coalition, plunged the government into an unprecedented political
crisis by voting in favor of an early-election bill in protest
against the government's failure to meet its demands for funding
its school network.
</P>
<P>
Barak caved in to Shas's increasing demands to keep the powerful
party in the coalition and save his shaky government from collapse.
But only when the three ministers from the pro-peace Meretz party,
also Shas's arch rival, tendered in their resignation did Shas
decide to stay.
</P>
<P>
The government crisis that Barak managed to tide over only re-
emerged when he badly needed the backing of his ruling partners
prior to the Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
Yisrael Ba'aliya headed by the former Interior Minister Natan
Sharasky, the National Religious Party and Shas quit the government
in succession, leaving the government with a minority 42 seats in
the Knesset. Barak himself held nine vacated portfolios in addition
to his own defense portfolio.
</P>
<P>
As political figures here put it, the country was run almost by
no government while Barak was at Camp David trying to hammer out a
peace deal with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Thus, to reshuffle his government is one of the top priorities
facing Barak after his return from the summit talks.
</P>
<P>
A much discussed option is to form a joint national coalition
with the opposition Likud, as Sharansky has been calling for.
Barak, however, may not take this into consideration as many
analysts believe because the inclusion of Likud in the coalition
might mean the end of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In response to Barak's call for a meeting with Likud party
leader Ariel Sharon on Thursday evening, a Likud spokesman quickly
poured cold water on speculations that they would forge a unity
government. The two former generals were due to meet late in the
day at the defense ministry in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, other Likud Knesset members also aired calls for an
early election, saying that Likud has no common grounds for forming
a joint coalition with Barak's One Israel.
</P>
<P>
Barak is going to face two no-confidence votes next Monday, one
submitted by Likud in protest against Barak's handling of the
negotiations, and the other by the United Arab List over the
government's negligence of the Palestinian rights.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, who has pledged continued efforts to pursue
a peace accord with the Palestinians, is likely to have his former
ruling partners back. Meretz on Thursday also expressed conditional
willingness to return to the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Politicians do widely agree that in the event of an eruption of
violent clashes with the Palestinians, there would definitely be a
need to form an emergency national unity government. Barak himself
also pondered this possibility while at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
However, during the meeting on Thursday night with Sharon, Barak
is expected to only brief him on the just-concluded summit and not
to raise the issue of forming the joint coalition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
