<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Seeks Mixed Court to Try Sierra Leonean War Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States Thursday
morning presented a draft resolution to the U.N. Security Council
in a bid to get the 15-nation council's approval to set up a mixed
Sierra Leonean-international tribunal to try Foday Sankoh, rebel
leader of Sierra Leone whose fighters have taken U.N. peacekeepers
hostage in early May, and his henchmen for accused war crimes.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Richard Holbrooke, U.S. permanent
representative to the United Nations, after he stepped out of the
Security Council Chamber.
</P>
<P>
The draft proposed a mixed Sierra Leonean-international court
to try people accused of war crimes in the war-torn West African
country, he said. In other words, the proposed tribunal will
comprise Sierra Leonean and international prosecutors and judges
and it will be paid by voluntary contributions.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador said that the draft was "endorsed in its
general framework by all the other" council members during closed-
door consultations and he hoped it would be voted on next week.
</P>
<P>
"It is very important that Foday Sankoh and his henchmen who
have committed these war crimes be brought to justice," Holbrooke
said.
</P>
<P>
The proposed court would be different from existing purely U.N.
tribunals set up to try alleged war criminals from the former
Yugoslavia and those accused of responsibility for the 1994
genocide in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The civil war in Sierra Leone, which broke out some nine years
ago and flared a new this year despite a peace accord signed in
July 1999 in Togo, has been marked by unusual brutality, with
rebels reportedly killing or mutilating thousands of civilians,
often chopping off their limbs.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, leader of the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF),
took up arms in 1991, signed the 1999 peace accord and is now in
government custody in Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
