<HEADLINE> Lott Moves to Proceed to China Trade Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott made a motion Wednesday, requesting the Senate to
proceed to the debate on the legislation granting permanent normal
trade relations (PNTR) status to China.
</P>
<P>
Lott said that while the measure was purely procedural, he
wanted to show his commitment to move the bill quickly when
Congress reconvenes in September.
</P>
<P>
"When we come back in September, this will be an issue that we
can go to soon rather than later in the month," he said.
</P>
<P>
A vote on the motion is expected Friday, the last day before
Congress recesses for the month of August.
</P>
<P>
Lott's motion, which is made under pressure of the White House
and the business community supporting the PNTR bill, will remove a
key hurdle to passage of the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to see the process move forward," U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky said. "Prompt action is
essential if the U.S. is to benefit from China's accession to the
WTO." 
</P>
