<HEADLINE> BT Profits Continue Fall On Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Stiff competition and the huge
costs of securing next generation mobile phone licenses have led
to a 27 percent slump in British Telecom (BT) profits.
</P>
<P>
Pre-tax profits for the quarter to June 30 fell to 561 million
pounds (370 million U.S. dollars) from 772 million pounds (510
million dollars) the time before, although turnover is up, to 6.8
billion pounds (4.5 billion dollars) from 5 billion pounds (3.3
billion dollars) last time.
</P>
<P>
BT also blames the fall in earnings on the cost of investing in
the Japanese and Irish telecoms markets and the expense last year
of taking complete control of BT Cellnet, when it bought a 40
percent stake from Securicor.
</P>
<P>
Robert Brace, BT group finance director, described the cost of
acquiring the UK third generation mobile phone license as "not the
best bargain of all time."
</P>
<P>
"The government has taxed the industry up front," he added.
Brace predicted the tough UK market conditions would continue,
with prices continuing their downwards trend.
</P>
<P>
However, the result was not as bad as had been feared by
analysts, and BT shares rose 10p to 878p in early trading Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
