<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S.Lanka's Constitutional Reforms Run Into Obstruction By Lian Guohui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's constitutional reforms
ran into obstruction from the main opposition United National
Party (UNP) on Thursday as the party decided to withdraw its
support in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The UNP, which holds the balance of power to make or break the
reforms, decided unanimously at its executive committee not to
deliver the promised votes in the parliament if the government
tries to rush President Chandrika Kumaratunga's controversial
constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
The constitutional reforms aim at politically ending the 17-
year civil war between government troops and Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels by devolving powers to provinces,
including one administered by minority Tamils.
</P>
<P>
The ruling People's Alliance (PA) of President Kumaratunga
needs the UNP's support in the parliament as it does not have the
two-thirds majority required to pass the reforms.
</P>
<P>
However, UNP spokesman Karunasena Kodituwakku said the
opposition is insisting that the government hold extensive talks
with all concerned parties before presenting the draft in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The UNP's widely expected decision could complicate problems
for the government which is already facing opposition from the
influential Buddhist clergy and Tamil parties.
</P>
<P>
The influential Buddhist clergy in this predominantly Buddhist
country and nationalist Sinhala organizations have said the
reforms are a sell-out to the minority and would lead to the
country's division.
</P>
<P>
Mainstream Muslim and Tamils parties, on their part, said the
reforms do not meet the political aspirations of the minority.
</P>
<P>
The UNP's leader Wickremesinghe last Friday quitted the
bipartisan talks with President Kumaratunga, saying he could not
take part as the government tried desperately to link him to the
LTTE rebels who have been fighting for a separate homeland for
minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
However, the UNP has reiterated that it will remain in talks
with the PA of Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
The two main parties, which have held a series of meetings
since March, have yet to agree on the transitional provisions in
the draft constitution that will abolish the executive presidency
and return Sri Lanka to a Westminister-style parliamentary system.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga has said she would present the draft
constitution before the parliament in early August and have it
adopted before the present parliament is dissolved automatically
on August 24 at the end of its six-year term.
</P>
<P>
Despite obstruction from the UNP, the Buddhist clergy and Tamil
parties, the government seems to be confident about the prospect
of the reforms.
</P>
<P>
"The discordant notes sounded by the opposition UNP, the
powerful Buddhist clergy and minority Muslim and Tamil parties
will soon die down and they will all come around, which could be
as early as August 4," Minister for Internal and International
Commerce and Food Kingsly Wicramaratne was quoted by press reports
as saying on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The opposition has always been buying time. With or without
their support, the president will make peace," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0057 </DOCNO>
