<HEADLINE> Moldova's GDP to Drop by 7 Percent in 2000: IMF Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product GDP)
of Moldova will drop by 7 percent in 2000 as a result of the
drought and the annual inflation rate will be 17-18 percent, the
Moldovan Basa-press news agency Wednesday quoted International
Monetary Fund (IMF) Regional Director Richard Haas as saying.
</P>
<P>
In early 2000, the National Bank of Moldova and the Finance
Ministry forecasted a 2-percent rise in the GDP and a 26-percent
inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the end of the IMF two-week
mission to Chisinau, Richard Haas said that in 2001 the GDP of
Moldova will rise by 5 percent and the annual inflation will drop
by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Based on these parameters, the IMF mission signed with the
Chisinau government an agreement on the 2000 budget that,
according to Haas, will be "financed from interior resources."
</P>
<P>
Moldovan Premier Dumitru Braghis told the same press conference
that the government will present rectifications to the 2000 budget
in late September. According to him, the main figures -- revenues,
expenses and deficit -- will not experience any changes.
</P>
<P>
Braghis said that 43.7 percent of the annual revenues were
collected in the first half of 2000. He said the Moldovan budget
has a seasonable character and two-thirds of the budget are
collected in the second half of the year. Braghis said he is
optimist and believes that the 2000 budget will be implemented
integrally. He added that in the opinion of IMF experts, the
cabinet will be forced, however, to take a 100-million-leu (an
about 8 million U.S. dollar) credit from the National Bank to
cover the budgetary deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
