<HEADLINE> Former Diplomat Sentenced to 11 Years in Jail for Espionage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Moscow City Court has sentenced
Platon Obukhov, a former Russian Foreign Ministry employee accused
of spying for Britain, to 11 years in jail for high treason.
</P>
<P>
The court has also ruled that Obukhov's property be confiscated,
the Interfax news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, Obukhov's lawyer Galina Krylova said the defense
intends to appeal to the Russian Supreme Court against Thursday's
court ruling. The lawyer believes that the evidence presented in
court was obtained with violations of the law.
</P>
<P>
Obukhov, the son of Alexei Obukhov, a former Russian deputy
foreign minister and Russian ambassador to Denmark, was arrested
by the Federal Security Service (FSB) in April 1996 on suspicion
of collaborating with British intelligence.
</P>
<P>
The former diplomat was earlier deemed as psychologically
irresponsible and on July 30, 1997, the Moscow City Court decided
to impose forced psychiatric treatment on him.
</P>
<P>
The Moscow City Court was to resume the hearing of his case in
February 2000 at the end of the forced treatment, but the court
postponed the hearing until now after an April 28 evaluation by
expert-psychiatrist Yevgeny Krylov that deemed Obukhov sane,
Interfax said. 
</P>
