<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Military Asked to Help Contain Blazes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Over 70 fires burned across parts of 10 Western states in the
United States Wednesday, racing through timber, grass and brush.
</P>
<P>
About half of the smaller fires had no crews on hand at all. In
some cases, calls for help with wildfires have been delayed or
unfilled for days because resources have been devoted to major
fires.
</P>
<P>
The wildfire season, which began when a prescribed brush-
clearing fire near Los Alamos, New Mexico State, raged out of
control and destroyed more than 200 homes in May, has become the
worst since 1996.
</P>
<P>
In hopes of gaining ground on the fires, Army soldiers will
attend crash courses in firefighting techniques organized by the
National Interagency Fire Center in Boise, Idaho State.
</P>
<P>
Center spokeswoman Lorraine Buck said the soldiers should be
ready to join fire lines next week, but he did not say how many
soldiers would end up on lines.
</P>
<P>
The last time the fire center mobilized military units was in
the summer of 1996, using 1,160 soldiers. Fires that year had
burned 1.2 million hectares by July 25. So far this year, fires
have burned 1.05 million hectares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
