<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Anti-Drug Police Seize 89.5 Kilograms of Heroin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Turkish anti-drug security forces
Thursday seized 89.5 kilograms of heroin in Baskale town, eastern
Van province bordering Iran.
</P>
<P>
Acting on a tip-off, the police raided several houses in Guroluk
village of the town and confiscated the drugs, one Kalashnikov
rifle and a hand gun, Anatolia News Agency reported. They also
arrested four suspects.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the police seized 2,328 roots of Indian hemp in the
Kayabogazi Yapili hamlet, another village under the Catak township
of Van province.
</P>
<P>
The hemps were set ablaze and investigations into the drugs are
underway, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Turkish chief police authority said the anti-
narcotics police had launched "determined and successful" struggle
against drugs trafficking via the country.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued amid some newspapers criticism that the
police carried out inefficient anti-drug operations.
</P>
<P>
The police authority summed up its latest operations and
dismissed the reports as "unrealistic and baseless."
</P>
<P>
In 1999, a total of 6,121 people were arrested in 2,587 separate
incidents while anti-drug forces impounded 2,249 kilograms of
heroin, 5,458 kilograms of hashish, 288 kilograms of base morphine,
13 kilograms of cocaine, 26.2 tons of acid anhydride and 1,749,305
captogan pills, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the forces captured 3,219 suspects in 1,458
operations and seized 2,850 kilograms of heroin, 22.6 tons of
hashish, 976 kilograms of base morphine, 56 kilograms of opium, 6
kilograms of cocaine, 5.5 tons of acid anhydride, 618,336 captogan
pills and 14,964 synthetic drugs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 1,583 kilograms of heroin, 50 kilograms of cocaine,
15.5 kilograms of opium and 8.3 tons of acid anhydride were
confiscated in joint operations with the U.S., German, British,
Romanian, Belgian, Russian, Dutch, Spanish, Italian and Greek anti-
narcotics units, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is a commercial and cultural bridge between Europe and
Asia because of its geographical position. Nearly 70 percent of
illicit drugs produced in the rest of the world are smuggled to
European countries via Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
