<HEADLINE> 3.7 Billion Dollars Pledged for Vietnam's Transportation Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign donors have pledged official
development assistance (ODA) loans of 3.7 billion U.S. dollars for
the development of Vietnam's transportation infrastructure in the
2001-2010 period, Vietnam's official news agency VNA reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the loans, 3.069 billion dollars will be spent on 19
projects of roads, 64.9 million dollars on three railway
construction projects, 71.8 million dollars on five river-way
projects, 362.4 million dollars on three projects to build and
upgrade seaports, and 136.2 million dollars on two projects to
upgrade urban traffic systems.
</P>
<P>
The main projects include Ho Chi Minh City's East-West road,
Thanh Tri bridge in Hanoi, Mekong delta's Can Tho bridge, Hai Van
tunnel and Hai Phong northern port.
</P>
<P>
In the 1993-1999 period, foreign donors pledged ODA loans of
more than 15 billion dollars for the country, 40 percent of which
was disbursed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
