<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wilson Grabs Early Lead in U.S. Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Blaine Wilson put himself in
good shape for a record fifth consecutive title at the U.S.
Gymnastics Championships in St. Louis Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Wilson was nearly flawless in the all-around preliminaries, not
scoring lower than 9.475 for any routine. His score of 58.225
points is more than a point ahead of Sean Townsend, a huge lead
going into the all-around finals on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't know it was that much," said Wilson, adding that "it'
s not the kind of thing where you relax."
</P>
<P>
Wilson won the floor exercise and vault Wednesday night, and
tied John Roethlisberger for first on the rings.
</P>
<P>
Townsend is second with 57.025 points, Stephen McCain came
third with 57.000 points and 17-year-old Paul Hamm fourth with 56.
525.
</P>
<P>
Jason Gatson, who was leading the all-around last year until
blowing out his knee on the horizontal bar, is in 19th place after
crashing on parallel bars, falling off the pommel horse and
touching his hands down on the floor exercise.
</P>
<P>
Other event champions include Roethlisberger on the pommel
horse and Trent Wells on the horizontal bar and parallel bars.
</P>
<P>
The top 14 men in the all-around will go to the Olympic trials
slated for August 17-20 in Boston. 
</P>
