<HEADLINE> Philippine Muslim Rebels Want Talks to Be Held on Neutral Soil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Moro Islamic Liberation Front (
MILF) has brushed aside the Philippine government's decision that
the resumption of peace talks with the government be held in the
country, the rebel group said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
MILF chief negotiator Aleem Abdulaziz Mimbantas made the group'
s stance clear in a written letter to his government counterpart
insisting that peace talks be held in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
But Egardo Batenga, government panel head, reiterated the
government's position that the talks be held in Philippine
territory as the problem being resolved by both panels is "
internal and needs no intervention from foreign countries."
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Bajunaid said that they are very much
willing to return to the negotiating table so long as there are no
preconditions set by the government, adding that the talks should
be pursued in accordance with the general framework of agreement
signed by both panels in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
On the MILF insistence to hold the talks outside the country,
Bajunaid stressed that the threat issued by Police Director
General Panfilo Lacson to arrest MILF leaders with pending
criminal cases, is "vexing."
</P>
<P>
Meantime, he confirmed that Al Haj Murad, the MILF vice
chairman for military affairs, is much alive and kicking, but he
refused to reveal Murad's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Murad was killed when his office in
Maguindanao province was bombarded by government troops in May.
</P>
<P>
Bajunaid said that "in fact the order to mount massive counter
offensive against military establishments even came from Murad."
</P>
<P>
He said that Ghadzali Jaafar and Mohaqher Iqbal, MILF vice
chair for political affairs and chief propagandist, respectively,
are out of the country while MILF Chairman Hashim Salamat has gone
to Cairo, Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
