<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Clothing Chain Shuts Down Shops in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Dutch clothing chain Kreymborg is
shutting its 12 Belgian shops after losing money in business,
local media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A group of more than 30 years, Kreymborg sells clothes for men
and women in its outlets in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Its mother company now is closing down and is shutting all its
49 Dutch and 12 Belgian shops. Kreymborg has been faced with major
losses for years, especially due to strong competition in the
clothing sector.
</P>
<P>
The management board of the chain said that none of their
employees will lose their jobs. So far, all Belgian Kreymborg
outlets but one will be taken over, five by the French clothing
chain Etam, one by Spanish group Zara and five by the Dutch
drugstore Kruidvat. They will also take over the staff of the
shops.
</P>
<P>
Only the shop in Belgium's west Flemish city of Kortrijk will
be closed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, French retailer chain Carrefour took over Belgian
retailer chain GB as part of a merger wave in 15 nations of the
European Union. Belgium, a traditionally welfare state, is
witnessing fierce competition from market economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
