<P>
BUCHAREST, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Private companies have greatly
contributed to the latest boom in Romanian exports, accounting for
61.8 percent of exports and 67.7 percent of imports, the local
daily Cronica Romana reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting figures from the Romanian National Commission on
Statistics, the paper said the total value of private companies'
exports in the first four months this year stood at 1.97 billion U.
S. dollars, with imports worth 2.39 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Romania's main trading partners continued to be the countries
in the European Union (EU). Romania's exports with the EU partners
totaled 2.04 billion U.S. dollars, or 68 percent of the whole
exports, that is a 21.4 percent year-on-year rise.
</P>
<P>
Imports from the EU countries reached 2.02 billion U.S. dollars,
or 60.7 percent of total imports, a 7.4 percent year-on-year
increase.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries are also Romania's important trading
partners, with 15.3 percent of the country's exports going there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
