<HEADLINE> North African Giants to Clash in Nations Cup Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- North African giants Morocco
and Tunisia were grouped together when the draw for the 2002
African Nations Cup qualifying competition was made in Cairo
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Morocco are ranked second behind South Africa on the continent
by world governing body Fifa and Tunisia are third. Gabon and
Kenya complete the Group 3 line-up.
</P>
<P>
The winners and runners-up of the seven mini-leagues qualify
for the finals in Mali, who gain automatic entry to the tournament
with defending champions Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
South Africa will not be overjoyed at sharing Group 2 with
George Weah-inspired Liberia, Congo and Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, beaten by Cameroon in a controversial penalty-shootout
climax to the 2000 Nations Cup, drew potential giantkillers
Madagascar and Namibia and two-time runners-up Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Ghana and Egypt, winners of the event a record four times each,
should not experience too many problems qualifying for the finals
of a tournament.
</P>
<P>
The Black Stars from Ghana look the strongest team in Group 6
beside fallen giants Democratic Republic of Congo, minnows Lesotho
and perennial underachievers Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Egypt face formidable Group 7 opposition in 1992 champions
Ivory Coast (Cote d'Ivoire), Libya and the Sudan. 
</P>
