<HEADLINE> U.S. Gymnastics Become a Battle of Generations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- When the women begin their
competition today at the U.S. Gymnastics Championships, five
members of the 1996 Olympic champion team are trying to beat a new
generation of more athletic breed.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1996 Olympians, only Amy Chow, 22, kept competing until
this year, and Shannon Miller, 23, was the biggest surprise since
she has already become the most successful U.S. gymnast winning
the most Olympic medals in history with two golds, two silvers and
three bronzes.
</P>
<P>
The other returnees were Jaycie Phelps, 20, Dominique Moceanu,
18, and Dominique Dawes, 23.
</P>
<P>
Challenging these veterans are two-time U.S. national all-
around champion Kristen Maloney, 19, Elise Ray, 18, the highest-
ranked U.S. gymnast at the 1999 World Championship, Vanessa Atler,
18, the vault champion and all-around runner-up at the 1999 U.S.
Championships, and 1999 U.S. World Championships team members of
Alyssa Beckerman, Jeanette Antolin, Jamie Dantzscher and Morgan
White.
</P>
<P>
At stake was the 12 top spots as they will advance to the
Olympic trials next month in Boston where the Olympic team will be
selected.
</P>
<P>
And it will be the first time for Bela Karolyi, who was
recalled to the national team last November as coordinator, to
inspect the women gymnasts in the pressure-packed competitions.
</P>
<P>
The United States finished a miserable sixth place at the World
Championships in China last October, an unacceptable fall for a
country that had taken the Olympic gold medal just three years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
