<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Compromise on Jerusalem, No Peace Agreement: Israeli Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- It is impossible to reach an
Israeli-Palestinian agreement without painful Israeli compromise on
the Jerusalem issue, Israel's left-wing Meretz party said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The secular Meretz maintained that any solution to the issue
should be based on "joint sovereignty," in which Israel controls
Jewish neighborhoods and the Palestinians control Arab villages in
East Jerusalem, party officials said.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were published following the failure of the Camp
David summit near Washington. The summit was designed to find
solutions to the final status issues to pave the way for a
permanent peace deal by September between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides failed to bridge their differences over core
issues, especially the fate of Jerusalem, during the 15 days of
rough talks.
</P>
<P>
The issue is intractable as Israel regards the holy city as
its "eternal and undivided" capital, while the Palestinians want to
secure at least the eastern part of the city, which Israel captured
during the 1967 Middle East war, as the capital of their own future
state.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side rejected all the proposals short of giving
the Palestinians full sovereignty over the Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meretz, which quitted Barak's government last month but has
vowed continued support for Barak's peace policy, is the most
dovish Israeli party regarding the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, scores of Meretz supporters
demonstrated near Israeli Defense Ministry in Tel Aviv Thursday
morning, urging Barak, who also holds the Defense portfolio, to
continue peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
Most of the demonstrators were youngsters under the age of
enlistment, who said they did not want to die in the next war --
referring to a possible violence between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has said that he would unilaterally declare an
independent Palestinian state if an agreement cannot be reached by
September 13 with Israel. It is feared that such a move might lead
to widespread violence, even a limited war, in the Israeli-occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's domestic firms are projected to produce 1.3
million color TV sets in the current Iranian year starting March
20, an increase of 35.8 percent compared with the previous Iranian
year.
</P>
<P>
The glut of TV sets in Iran necessitate promotion of export, a
local official was quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency as
saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official said that Iran-made TV sets enjoy a desirable level
of quality and are quite able to compete with foreign products.
</P>
<P>
Domestic production of various kinds of color television sets
saves the country some 80 million U.S. dollars annually, he added.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey imports are likely to exceed 48 billion U.S.
dollars in 2000, 2 billion higher than an earlier projection in the
government program, reported Turkish Daily News on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government set an export target at 28.3 billion dollars and
a huge foreign trade deficit is taking shape.
</P>
<P>
Five-month imports, according to figures released by the State
Statistics Organization Wednesday, totaled 20.4 billion dollars, up
37.6 percent from the same period in 1999 while exports over the
same period rose by a mere 4.8 percent to 11.2 billion. The deficit
reached 9.2 billion, up 122 percent compared to last year.
</P>
<P>
The State Minister responsible for the economy Tunca Toskay said
that Turkey would resort to effective trade policies such as quota,
supervision, anti-dumping and standardization to curb the sharp
deficit increase.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq's first computer center opened here on Thursday,
which would allow ordinary Iraqis to surf the Internet for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Transport and Communications Ahmad Murtadha
Ahmad Khalil cut the ribbon at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has lagged far behind in information technology, with
people having had no access to the Internet, mainly due to the
sweeping sanctions imposed by the United Nations in 1990 after its
invasion of neighboring Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
