<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2nd APEC Youth Science Festival Opens in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The 2nd APEC Youth Science
Festival (AYSF) opened here Thursday with the participation of 592
middle school students aged 15 to 18 and 213 teachers and
delegates from 15 economies of the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC).
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation, consisting of 49 students and 18
educators from Beijing, Shanghai and Shanxi Province, is the
biggest in size after Singapore which is the host.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister for Education and Second Minister for
Defense Teo Chee Hean made an opening speech and Executive
Director of the APEC Secretariat Serbini Ali delivered a
congratulatory message at the opening ceremony featuring
colorfulness, dances and instrumental music.
</P>
<P>
Teo said the 2nd AYSF demonstrates APEC's emphasis on
education as a key strategy to lead toward economic prosperity and
will provide an opportunity for students from different APEC
economies to learn and work together and appreciate each other's
culture.
</P>
<P>
"By getting our youths to learn about science together, we hope
to build a network of future technoprenuers, scientists and
leaders whose work will benefit future generations, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Serbini said in his message that this youth festival is "a
direct response to the APEC Leaders' call to harness the vast
potential of human capital in building a knowledge-based society."
</P>
<P>
The one-week festival seeks to enhance the intellectual and
creative interests of APEC youths in science and technology and to
provide opportunities for them to exchange knowledge of science
and culture.
</P>
<P>
With Singapore as its host, the festival has brought together
a total of 805 local and foreign students and educators from 15
participating economies, namely Australia, Brunei, China, Hong
Kong, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, New Zealand, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, Chinese Taipei, the United
States and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
A three and half-day science &AMP; technology exhibition, which is
on the top of the agenda and, also opened this morning to showcase
projects and displays by students participants in their scientific
investigations covering the five categories of clean environment,
communications, diversity, interactions and new endeavors.
</P>
<P>
The projects and displays demonstrated by the Chinese students
on 12 booths of the exhibition attracted a lot of visitors.
</P>
<P>
At the festival there will be a Youth Science Summit which is a
platform for participants to discuss issues, make recommendations
and propose solutions to the problems and challenges facing the
mankind in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda are cultural exchanges during which each
participating economy will present a cultural item, science
investigation activities in which the students participants will
be divided into 15 groups to explore the biodiversity at 15 spots
of the island of Singapore, lectures to be given by professors
from Singapore as well as some other countries, visits to
Singapore Science Center, historical sites as well as R&AMP;D
institutions and universities.
</P>
<P>
There are also programs for the teacher participants to visit
schools and to participate science teacher seminar.
</P>
<P>
South Korea hosted the first AYSF in 1998 with participation by
some 500 students and teachers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
