<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Vows to Eradicate Polio in Three Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has vowed to
eradicate polio in three years, newspapers here reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
To reach the goal, vaccination against polio will be
deliberately focused on districts sharing borders with Tanzania's
neighbors, said Caroline Akim of the Expanded Program on
Immunization at a seminar here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
No polio cases had been traced in the country in the last two
years, the manager was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We are now convinced that by the year 2003, Tanzania will be a
polio-free area," Akim said.
</P>
<P>
According to Akim, before the formal declaration of polio
eradication, a team of local experts will conduct a national
survey to satisfy themselves that the disease has been wiped off
from Tanzania's face. Then, an international team will come to see
for themselves whether polio has been wiped out in the country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Ministry of Health of Tanzania had announced to
spend around 1.5 million U.S. dollars on conducting immunization
of polio and measles in 19 regions in the country this year.
</P>
<P>
Polio vaccines will be given to children between one day and
five years old.
</P>
<P>
Polio is a crippling disease, caused by wild polio virus. The
disease can be prevented if the sanitary and hygiene conditions
are improved and especially if the children are vaccinated during
the first year of life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bad Weather Costs Belgian Farmers' Incomes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This has been estimated by the country's largest farmer union,
de Boerenbond. Other experts estimate the damages to be even
higher.
</P>
<P>
During the past weeks, there were too much rains in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
According to the experts, most of the wheat in the country will
have to be used for animal fodder since the quality of wheat is
too poor for bakers to use. Furthermore, the farmers will have to
fork out more money to let the wheat dry.
</P>
<P>
Other grains are also suffering from the constantly wet weather.
Grains are growing more slowly than they normally do.
</P>
<P>
The union is asking Belgian Agriculture Minister Jaak Gabriels
to look into ways of helping the hard-hit farmers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Agriculture Department has pointed out that
farmers' damages can be included in tax claims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
