<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium to Revise Rules over Aircraft Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Belgian Federal Minister of
Transportation Isabelle Durant will revise the takeoff and landing
procedures of the planes in Belgian airports, local media said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister's announcement came after the Concorde crash near
Paris which killed 109 people on board and four on the ground.
</P>
<P>
The minister said most plane crashes happen just after taking
off or before landing. A study group of experts has been set up in
the transportation ministry to propose measures to improve safety
and to curb noise pollution around the airports, he said, adding
that the experts have two months to do their research.
</P>
<P>
The minister will then negotiate under results of the research
with people mainly living near the Brussels international airport,
the pilots and the airline companies about the revision of plane
maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
Durant also said that Belgium will not impose a ban on Concorde
planes because the supersonic aircraft rarely calls on Belgian
airports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
