<HEADLINE> HK Stocks Plunge Nearly One Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks fell nearly one
percent Thursday as investors took a sharp fall on Wall Street as
their cue to take profits on recent gains.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that most of the major stocks were consolidating
today, but buying was focused on the telecom conglomerates PCCW
and Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT. Investors were keen to pick up China-
related stocks, although the H-share and red chip indices fell
amid profit taking on recent leaders, they said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Hang Seng Index closed 0.97 percent or 170.14
points lower at 17,450.09, after falling to as low as 17,285.87 in
morning trade.
</P>
<P>
The turnover was thin at 14.293 billion HK dollars (1.832
billion U.S. dollars), down from 15.314 billion HK dollars on the
previous trading day.
</P>
<P>
Of the four sub-indexes of the HSI, Utilities rose 1.50 percent,
while Finance Properties and Commerce &AMP; Industry all lost 0.47
percent, 1.05 percent and 1.42 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Hang Seng China Enterprises Index and Hang Seng China-
Affiliated Corp Index continued to drop by 2.63 percent and 1.35
percent.
</P>
<P>
Hang Seng IT Index fell 0.70 percent while Hang Seng IT
Portfolio Index gained 0.21 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
