<HEADLINE> Canberra Continues Efforts to Restore Democracy in Fiji: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Canberra continues its efforts to
restore the Chaudhry government in Fiji.
</P>
<P>
The Associated Press reported that Australian Prime Minister
John Howard said Thursday he would continue to push for the
restoration of Mahendra Chaudhry as elected Fijian prime minister
but did not expect Australia to become directly involved in the
restoration of democracy.
</P>
<P>
He denied an accusation from Fiji's latest appointed Prime
Minister Laisena Qarase who reportedly accused Australia and New
Zealand early Thursday of a "threatening and aggressive" stance
towards his country and called for sanctions imposed by the two
nations to be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Howard said he was not aware of Mr. Qarase's remarks, but that
the accusation was wrong. "The measures we have imposed are not
damaging economic sanctions (but) we have said that there could be
further action taken if there is not a return to democratic rule,"
he said. 
</P>
