<HEADLINE> Anwar's Supporters Asked Not to Cause Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Inspector-General
of Police Norian Mai Thursday called on supporters of former
deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim not to do anything that could
undermine the country's peace and security on August 4 when the
High Court here delivers its judgment in Anwar's sodomy trial.
</P>
<P>
Police would take appropriate action to prevent the occurrence
of any undesirable incidents that day, the police chief told
reporters after a function here.
</P>
<P>
"I want to stress that we will take appropriate action to
ensure that a situation does not occur that can threaten security
or escalate into a bigger threat. I appeal to (Amwar's) supporters
and sympathizers to respect the law and not do anything to
jeopardize the situation in the court and its surroundings," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Prime Minister and Home Minister Abdullah
Ahmad Badawi Thursday warned of action against Anwar's supporters
if they hold unlawful assemblies on August 4.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah asked them to abandon their plans to hold
demonstrations on that day.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, 52, and his adopted brother, Sukma Darmawan Sasmitaat
Madja, 39, are charged with sodomizing Azizan Abu Bakar, 39, the
former driver of Anwar's wife Wan Azizah Ismail. 
</P>
