<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Economy Back More than Eight Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The two month long political
crisis set Fiji's economy back more than eight years.
</P>
<P>
According to the Australian Associated Press, Fijian Minister
for Finance Ratu Jone Kubuabola said in a mini-budget address that
"it takes the economy back to where it was at the end of 1991."
</P>
<P>
Economic growth is forecast at a negative 15 percent this year,
in stark contrast to Fiji's new year projection of a positive four
percent.
</P>
<P>
One of the major industry earners, tourism, has been sharply
affected and arrivals are now projected to fall by more than 50
percent from the record levels seen in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The annual rate of inflation was now expected to rise to five
percent, compared to a negative rate before the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The situation will deteriorate further," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry is now proposing tough cost-cutting
measures in line with a destined decline in revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Expects Good Economic Growth for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore economy is
expected to grow by 5.5 percent to 7.5 percent this year, the
Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) said Thursday in its annual
report.
</P>
<P>
The MAS attributed the projected growth to continued strong
increase in exports, sustained recovery in consumption and a
turnaround in investments.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the growth momentum to be sustained for the rest of
2000 and to moderate only slightly next year," said Koh Yong Guan,
managing director of MAS, at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"This is underpinned by the favorable outlook for the external
economic environment. Economic activity will be led by steady
growth in the manufacturing sector and a strong pick-up in the
services sectors, " Koh said.
</P>
<P>
Gross Domestic Product (GDP) expanded at a robust pace of 9.1
percent in the first quarter of 2000, with growth propelled
largely by the manufacturing sector, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"Domestic spending is also expected to remain strong. We expect
the remaining slack in the economy to be taken up within the next
twelve months," Koh added.
</P>
<P>
Growth of the commerce and transport and communications sectors
also strengthened, while the financial services returned to
positive growth, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the only sector that continued to see
negative growth in the first quarter of 2000 was the construction
sector, which recorded double-digit declines in both private and
public construction activities.
</P>
<P>
As for regions outside Singapore, the report foresees "bright"
economic outlook for 2000 as private consumption is expected to
stay strong and consumer confidence continues to improve.
</P>
<P>
Stronger economies of Europe and Japan should offset any
slowdown in U.S. economic growth, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report also said the continuing boom in global electronics
demand also favors Asian exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ARF Participants See Positive Effects, Repercussions of Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the statement, they said while the security outlook for the
Asia-Pacific region remained positive, there were uncertainties
and challenges, posed particularly by globalization.
</P>
<P>
By positive effects and repercussions, they said that included
greater economic interdependence among nations and multiplication
of security issues.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, they stressed, it is necessary for nations to
strengthen their individual and collective capacities so as to
gain the capacity to meet the challenges affecting their common
security which comprises among other the economic, social and
human components.
</P>
<P>
As a step in the direction, they said they further agreed on
the need for the countries in the region to continue efforts, "
through dialogue and cooperation, at national and international
levels" to address the economic, social and political impact
bought about by globalization.
</P>
<P>
Only by so doing, they stressed, could the sustained economic
and social development be ensured and Asia-Pacific peace enhanced
within its frameworks.
</P>
<P>
ARF was initiated in 1993 by the ASEAN members with the aim to
facilitate and promote consultations on security issues among
entities of the Asia-Pacific region. China became its full member
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea is ARF's newest
member whose first appearance at the current meeting is widely
welcomed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
