<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Hits Northwest Capital City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Since mid July, a heat wave has
hit Lanzhou, the capital of northwest China's Gansu Province,
which is known for its cool summers.
</P>
<P>
The city has experienced the hottest days of the season with
mercury touching 39.8 degrees Celsius, 4.6 degrees above normal,
setting a record high since 1932.
</P>
<P>
The heat wave drove up the sales of electric fans, air
conditioners, sunstroke prevention medicines, drinks and
watermelon.
</P>
<P>
Lanzhou, an ideal place for spending a cool summer in the past
has become a furnace this summer. An elderly woman said she never
experienced such a hot summer in Lanzhou since she lived in 30
years.
</P>
<P>
A swimming pool in the city had more 3,000 people a day. The Ya
'ou Department Store, Lanzhou's largest one, sold out 70 to 80 air
conditioners a day.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals have treated dozens of people suffering from
sunstroke. Some local residents even booked rooms in air-
conditioned hotels to avoid the heat wave, which is expected to
last two or three more days.
</P>
<P>
A tourist from Chongqing said he originally planned to travel
to Lanzhou to spend a cool summer, but it seemed that he "fell
into a furnace". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
