<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqis Gain Access to Internet as First Computer Center Opens EDS-2nd lead-writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's first computer center was
opened here on Thursday, which would allow ordinary Iraqis to surf
the Internet for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Transport and Communications Ahmad Murtadha
Ahmad Khalil cut the ribbon at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has lagged far behind in information technology, with
people having had no access to the Internet, mainly due to the
sweeping sanctions imposed by the United Nations in 1990 after its
invasion of neighboring Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
"Our decision is to do our best to serve our people and give
them as much as we can. That is why we provide them with this
service," Khalil told the foreign and local media.
</P>
<P>
Khalil said his ministry has been making efforts to open more
computer centers and increase the number of computers to facilitate
the users.
</P>
<P>
The center is located in the Saadoun street in central Baghdad,
and it is expected that another four such centers will be opened in
the Iraqi capital soon.
</P>
<P>
Khalil told Xinhua that the charge for Internet services has not
been decided yet, but it will be known by the end of this week. "I
do not think it costs a lot," he said.
</P>
<P>
It is said that using the Internet costs about 2,000 Iraqi
dinars (one U.S. dollar) an hour.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the computer center should have been
opened a long time ago. He blamed the delay on "obstacles" placed
by the United States and British delegates at the United Nations
Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
For the past seven phases of the U.N. oil-for-food program, only
12 percent of the contracts his ministry signed with foreign
countries were approved, Khalil said.
</P>
<P>
What is worse, the U.S. and British representatives at the
committee "did not approve one dollar for Iraq's telecommunications
sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. oil-for-food deal allows Iraq to sell crude to finance
imports of food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies to
alleviate the impacts of the decade-old sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has often accused the U.S. and Britain of blocking the
implementation of the U.N. program by putting on hold contracts it
signed with foreign countries, worsening the humanitarian crisis in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
