<HEADLINE> International Donor Meeting Opens in Beirut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-eight countries and
representatives from more than a dozen regional and international
lending institutions and humanitarian groups attended the
international donor conference that opened Thursday morning in
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Salim Hoss and the U.N. Middle East envoy Terje
Roed-Larsen co-chaired the one-day meeting, which is designed to
attract money for the development of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon hopes to raise 260 million U.S. dollars at the
conference for the reconstruction in south Lebanon which saw the
withdrawal of Israeli troops in May after a 22-year occupation. But
the premier has admitted in advance that it is not likely to
produce any immediate financial pledges at the meeting on the
ambassadorial level.
</P>
<P>
He told those participants that the people in south Lebanon are
in dire need of the help from international community so they can
restore their regular life and live with dignity.
</P>
<P>
"We Lebanese do not think the international community has made
full efforts to stop as early as possible Israel's occupation on
Lebanese territory, which is stipulated in several U.N.
resolutions. This delay let Lebanon to bear the disastrous result
of occupation and our economy was suffered by the war," he added.
</P>
<P>
As to the plan of aid, he explained that the government
formulated a two-step program. "The first urgent aid program is
aimed for life requirement and the second is to improve people's
life and set economical and social infrastructure there."
</P>
<P>
Lebanon will hold another donor meeting in October on the
ministerial level when the donors are scheduled to pledge the
amount of donations. Lebanon hopes to get more than 1.2 billion U.
S. dollars from donors, mainly European and Arab countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
