<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Switzerland Welcome U.S. Court Ruling on Holocaust Settlement Sum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss government, bankers and
representatives of Jewish organizations have welcomed Wednesday's
approval by a U.S. judge of the terms of a 1.25-billion-dollar
settlement between the Swiss banks and Holocaust victims for funds
blocked in Switzerland since the Nazi era.
</P>
<P>
In his ruling, Judge Edward Korman gave the banks and claimants
a week to resolve the remaining outstanding points of the
agreement, but said it would then take effect.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss government greeted Korman's decision by saying the
ruling "represents a decisive step toward formal closure of the
relevant judicial proceedings against the two Swiss banks in the U.
S."
</P>
<P>
The government also said that the settlement "provides for a
complete legal and material resolution of Second World War related
issues for the Swiss economy as well as Swiss public entities."
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, Switzerland's two main banks, UBS and
Credit Suisse, said, "the verdict reached by the U.S. district
judge, Korman, has cleared the way for the settlement to be made."
</P>
<P>
"We hope that those Holocaust survivors or their heirs with an
entitlement to the money from the fund will receive the amounts
they are due as soon as possible," said the two banks, which
agreed to the terms with the lawyers for plaintiffs in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
The settlement means that the money could soon be disbursed
among about 600,000 claimants. But it is not clear when the
distribution plan will be finalized.
</P>
<P>
"The chapter seems to be closed," said Sigi Feigel, honorary
president of Federatong, Switzerland's main Jewish organization.
</P>
<P>
The claimants said they or their relatives deposited the funds
in Swiss banks as a safe haven during the wartime era, but were
unable to retrieve the money and other goods after the war.
</P>
<P>
The Volcker commission, investigating the issue of dormant
accounts, concluded last year that up to 54,000 may have been
opened in Swiss banks by Holocaust victims. It cleared the banks
of systematically destroying the records of victims' accounts, but
said there was evidence of "deceitful actions by some banks".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
