<HEADLINE> Rios Defaulted at Mercedes-Benz Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Chilean Marcelo Rios, angered
when his opponent served before he was ready, and was defaulted in
the first round for swearing at the chair umpire on Wednesday at
the Mercedes-Benz Cup in Los Angeles, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Third-seed Rios trailed 5-3 behind in the first set against
Goichi Motomura of Japan when he called for time as Motomura
launched an ace. Rios said he was not ready to receive the serve,
but chair umpire Tony Nimmons rejected Rios' claim.
</P>
<P>
Rioa used an obscene word during the argument with Nimmons, who
called in ATP Tour supervisor Gayle Bradshaw. After conferring
with Nimmons, Bradshaw defaulted Rios.
</P>
<P>
Rios will lose $3,500 in prize money, his free hotel
accommodation and additional fines in accordance with the ATP Tour
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Motomura will play Australian Jason Stoltenberg on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
