<HEADLINE> Manila Eyes More IT Job Opportunities for Filipinos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Thursday that the Information Technology (IT) agreements signed in
the United States during the working visit of President Joseph
Estrada would provide more job opportunities for young Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said in press release here
that the agreements witnessed by President Estrada in San
Francisco, the first leg of his working visit, would benefit the
labor force, a large part of which is already IT-oriented.
</P>
<P>
"We might not hear about it, but so many of our fellow
Filipinos are being employed in IT companies. Some of them are
simple, but very well-paying," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government has laid down the foundations for
IT, as shown by the mushrooming of many new technology centers in
the country.
</P>
<P>
These include centers in Clark and Subic in Central Luzon, and
Eastwood, Fort Bonifacio and Filinvest in southern Metro Manila.
</P>
<P>
Zamora cited America Online (AOL), one of the world's largest
Internet service providers, which employs Filipinos to handle
technical support calls.
</P>
<P>
"AOL employs more than 1,000 people in the Philippines," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Zamora, the president has witnessed the signing of
five agreements between Philippine and U.S. firms during his visit.
</P>
<P>
Estrada left here Monday night for his eight-day first official
working visit to the United States in an effort to further cement
bilateral ties and cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
