<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall Sharply in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell sharply in Tokyo
Thursday, dragged down by high-priced information and technology
issues which faced selling following Wednesday's decline on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 320.60 points, or 1.94
percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 16,182.01.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, fell 26.70 points, or 1.77 percent, to 1,477.
83, closing below 1,500 for the first time in more than nine
months.
</P>
<P>
Uncertainty over the Japanese economy following the collapse of
Sogo Co. and fears about an imminent end to the zero-interest-rate
policy by the Bank of Japan have made investors hesitant to buy
stocks, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 531.39 million
shares from Wednesday's 507.44 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nomura Securities was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Information technology issues fell after New York's Nasdaq
composite index closed below 4,000 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hit by recent weakness in share prices, brokerage firms were
the biggest losers, falling 7.56 percent as a group,
</P>
<P>
The paper, rubber and real estate sectors also weakened, while
the air and land transportation sectors were firm on expectations
that travel demand will increase in the summer holiday season,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far
outnumbered gainers 976 to 292, while 124 issues closed unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
