<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- After meeting with Shas leader Eli Yishai at the Knesset
(parliament) Wednesday, Israel's Likud presidential candidate Moshe
Katsav told the Jerusalem Post that Shas and the presidency are "in
my pocket."
</P>
<P>
Yishai did not make any promise in advance of Shas spiritual
leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef's decision on whether to endorse a
candidate or give his legislators freedom to vote, but Katsav said
he emerged from the meeting confident that Shas' 17 votes will
bring him victory in the secret ballot in the Knesset on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, back in Israel Wednesday
after the collapse of the Camp David summit, believes that
negotiations with the Palestinians will resume within the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Barak believes that both Israel and the Palestinians have a
common interest in preventing any deterioration into a violent
conflict over a unilateral Palestinian declaration of independence.
</P>
<P>
At a short ceremony at Ben-Gurion Airport, Barak said that "In
your names, in the names of the millions of eyes still looking,
hoping and praying, I promise not to despair, not to tire, not to
stop pursuing peace."
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat received a hero's welcome
when he landed at the Gaza Strip International Airport Wednesday,
returning home after two weeks of peace talks at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
Arafat stopped off in Alexandria for a meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak. At the end of the one-hour meeting, Arafat
said "the (Camp David) talks were especially difficult, not just
over Jerusalem, but also over the right of refugees to return to
their homes."
</P>
<P>
"We came with the determination not to cede our rights.
Jerusalem is not only for the Palestinians, it is for the
Palestinians, for the Arab nations, for the Christians, and for
Muslims everywhere," he later told reporters in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Barak has decided that he must set up a coalition that will
pursue the peace process, and that he will consider a national
unity government only if violence with the Palestinians seems
imminent, a source close to him said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Barak said Wednesday night that he would deal with coalition
matters Thursday. The best option right now seems to be to absorb
both Shas and Meretz into the cabinet, without former coalition
partners Yisrael Ba'aliya and the National Religious party.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Barak is also preparing for the possibility of
forming a national unity government with Likud. Barak phoned Likud
Chairman Ariel Sharon Wednesday night to invite him to a meeting
Thursday evening "for an update on the Camp David summit." 
</P>
