<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ten thousand Officials Demoted for Incompetence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- More than 10,000 Chinese officials
at or above the county level have been demoted or removed from
their posts for incompetence over the past five years, according
to sources from the Ministry of Personnel.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the central authorities and local governments
have paid much emphasis to deepening the reforms of the personnel
system, in which the capable are promoted and the incompetent
demoted.
</P>
<P>
This has fundamentally changed the previous cadre management
system in which only those who made mistakes are demoted or
removed.
</P>
<P>
Some provinces, including North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, have established new ways of cadre assessment.
From 1996 to 1999, over 260 officials in the region stepped down
for poor performances.
</P>
<P>
In the Central China provinces of Hunan and Hubei, a probation
system for officials has been widely adopted. Those who prove
incompetent after working for a certain time on trial basis, are
removed from posts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Five Chinese cities, namely Beijing, Shijiazhuang, Taiyuan,
Changsha and Xining, reported slight air pollution today, with the
highest pollutant indicator reading at 138.
</P>
<P>
According to a daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center, level-two, or fairly good air
quality, was found in the following 30 cities: Tianjin, Hohhot,
Shenyang, Dalian, Harbin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong,
Hangzhou, Wenzhou, Hefei, Fuzhou, Xiamen, Nanchang, Jinan, Qingdao,
Yantai, Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Guangzhou, Shantou, Zhanjiang, Chongqing,
Chengdu, Guiyang, Lhasa, Xi'an, Yinchuan and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulates less than 10 microns in size were the major
pollutants in most of the cities, except Chongqing and Guiyang,
where sulfur dioxide was the major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Six cities, namely Changchun, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Nanning, Haikou
and Kunming, reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level-one or excellent (pollution readings: not
exceeding 50), level-two or fairly good (pollution readings: 51 to
100), level-three or slightly polluted (pollution readings: 101-
200), level-four or poor (pollution readings: 201-300), and level-
five or hazardous (pollution readings: over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored by the center include the four
municipalities of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing,
provincial capitals and major cities in the economically developed
coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
