<HEADLINE> South Korea Begins Arctic Ocean Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean expedition team left
Seoul Thursday for the Arctic Ocean to make a joint research with
Russian scientists.
</P>
<P>
The team will reach the Arctic Ocean next Tuesday on board a
Russian ice breaker traveling to the Barents and Kara Seas, and
spend 26 days there to collect ocean deposits to study the
greenhouse effect and climate changes on earth, the Maritime
Affairs and Fisheries Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The team will join the International Arctic Science Committee,
a non-governmental organization aimed at facilitating cooperation
in Arctic research, and build a research station on the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time for a South Korean expedition team to
leave for the North Pole. 
</P>
