<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global E-Commerce Penetration Stands at 10 Percent, Study Reveals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A worldwide study of e-
commerce released Wednesday found that among Internet users around
the globe, about 10 percent shop online during a month.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 15 percent of Internet users say they have
considered shopping online, but have not yet done so, according to
the study conducted by Taylor Nelson Sofres (TNS) Interactive, a U.
S.-based Internet research business. The findings are based on
more than 30,000 interviews in 27 countries and regions on four
continents.
</P>
<P>
The study found that the United States has the highest
proportion of Internet users, with 58 percent of the population,
and also the highest proportion of shoppers online, 27 percent. In
contrast, only 1 percent of users currently shop online in both
Thailand and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"The potential for online shopping among existing Internet
users worldwide may realistically double in a relatively short
time if those users who say they have considered shopping online,
but have not yet done so, can be turned into actual shoppers,"
said the TNS.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, there are clearly a number of barriers
to overcome before online shopping can really take off globally.
The Internet is still a relatively new channel for most users and
many are still skeptical about it. E-commerce businesses need to
give more thought to how they present the online shopping
experience to potential customers. Local governments and tax laws
also stand in the way.
</P>
<P>
The study found interesting local differences among Internet-
related shopping behaviors in different countries and regions. In
India, for example, 83 percent of users have never shopped online
and have no plans to do so, compared with 36 percent in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The largest purchase of food and grocery products online is in
Hong Kong (32 percent of users), the largest online business of
leisure travel is in France (44 percent). Toiletries and
cosmetics online business catches the most shoppers in Japan (12
percent), compared with virtually none in the U.K.
</P>
<P>
Internet users in France buy the most stock and mutual funds
online -- 17 percent, compared with 2 percent in the U.K. More
than one in five of online shopping in the United States relates
with clothing items compared with 10 percent in the U.K. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
