<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, July 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Cell phones have changed the way Americans live, providing
them with convenience, productivity and a sense of security," said
the international association for the wireless telecommunications
industry.
</P>
<P>
The industry continues to grow at the rate of more than 67,000
new wireless subscribers every day, said the association, adding
that the American customers have choices with 86 percent of them
choosing between three or more wireless carriers.(US-Wireless-
Subscribers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Inter-American Development Bank (IDB)
announced Wednesday the approval of a soft loan of 15 million U.S.
dollars to Nicaragua to help finance new investments in a
wastewater treatment program for the city of Managua to meet new
design requirements that resulted from the severe flooding of
Hurricane Mitch in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In other action, the Washington-based bank approved a loan of 1
million dollars to strengthen the institutional capacity of the
Ministry of Family Affairs and to transfer responsibilities for
assisting society's most vulnerable groups to civil society
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Both loans are for a 40-year term, with a 10-year grace period,
at an annual interest rate of 1 percent during the grace period
and 2 percent thereafter. (IDB-Nicaragua-Loans)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuelan government warned Wednesday that it will
grant oil exploitation concessions in the Esequibo territory, now
under Guyanese sovereignty but reclaimed by Venezuela, if the
Georgetown authorities insist in doing the same and install a U.S.
aerospace base there.
</P>
<P>
Venezuelan Foreign Minister Jose Vicente Rangel explained that
Guyana has granted concessions for oil and timber exploitation
that violate the Geneva Convention that regulates the relations
between both countries, conditioned by the territorial reclamation.
(Venezuela-Concessions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON - Business confidence among manufacturers in Britain is
falling at the fastest rate for 18 months, according to the
Confederation of British Industry (CBI).
</P>
<P>
In its quarterly survey of industrial trends released Wednesday,
the CBI said both business confidence and optimism over exports
were plummeting.
</P>
<P>
A total of 21 percent of manufacturers were less optimistic
than four months ago, and only 11 percent more confident. This
gave an overall figure of -10 percent, as opposed to -2 percent in
April. (UK-Business-CBI)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said on
Wednesday that first high-level meeting of the "Global Compact"
had been very stimulating and that the participants had agreed to
a number of steps to take the "Global Compact" further.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference following the conclusion of the meeting,
Annan said "We are off to a good start," noting that the progress
made at the meeting would help make the Compact truly global and
operational.
</P>
<P>
First initiated by the Secretary-General at the World Economic
Forum in Davos in January 1999, the "Global Compact" challenges
world business leaders to promote and apply nine widely accepted
principles. (UN-Annan-Initiative) 
</P>
