<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Hold First Biennial Conference on Science, Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will hold its first ever
biennial conference on science and technology next month in a bid
to enable the island country to meet globalization challenges,
press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The conference is organized by the National Science and
Technology Commission (NASTEC) and the Ministry of Science and
Technology. It will be held from August 24 to 27 under the theme
of "Science and Technology for National Development."
</P>
<P>
"Our country only contribute 0.15 percent from the GDP to
science and technology," Chairman of the NASTEC R.O.B. Wijesinghe
was quoted by The Island newspaper as saying. He said more
developed countries like South Korea and Malaysia are contributing
about 2 percent to this field.
</P>
<P>
Wijesinghe said a report would be prepared drawing the final
recommendations of the conference and develop a Science and
Technology Agenda for national development. It will then be
presented to the president through the science and technology
minister for implementation by all the involved ministers, he said.
</P>
<P>
The conference will focus on developing a significant science
and technology capability in relevant thrust areas and determine
the priorities for investment in research and development. It will
cover areas including agriculture, health, environment, education,
industry and information technology and financing.
</P>
<P>
Participants will comprise leading scientists from universities
and research institutes, directors of research institutes, heads
of departments, industrial leaders of the private sector,
departmental scientists, social scientists, secretaries of
ministries, bankers and entrepreneurs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
