<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Enterprises Seek Business Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Fourteen enterprises in north
China's largest port city Tianjin invested some 14 million U.S.
dollars abroad in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
This has added the total number of enterprises investing
overseas to 340 in the municipality, involving a total investment
of 216 million U.S. dollars in 72 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Of the 340 enterprises, 187 are trade related. 24 are engaged
in service industry and 53 are production firms.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Tianjin-funded production enterprises are based in
Africa, some East European countries, and Cuba. Their projects
involve pharmaceuticals, ice creams, bicycles, plastic articles
and textile.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Tianjin Municipal Foreign Trade and
Economic Commission said though flowing-in investment still
surpasses flowing-out funds, there has been a rapid growth in the
latter.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government is planning to introduce more
preferential policies to encourage companies in light industry,
textiles, household electric appliances, machinery and electronics
and clothing to set up joint ventures overseas, particularly in
East Europe, Africa and Middle Asia.  
</P>
