<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China News Digest: West on the Move (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has launched projects to tackle the environment-damaged
Tarim River, the longest inland river in the country.
</P>
<P>
One of the project is to divert water from the Bosten Lake,
which is 580 kilometers away, into the river in Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, northwest China. The project can at least water
100 kilometers of the dry lower reaches of the Tarim River,
according to engineers of the project.
</P>
<P>
Other projects, involving 200 million yuan (20.09 million U.S.
dollars), will include building a 800-kilometer-long dyke and more
than 60 water gates along the middle reaches of the Tarim River.
</P>
<P>
The regional government is also drafting a program on
harnessing the river. The plan, to be completed within three years,
covers ecological protection, development of agriculture, animal
husbandry and aquatic production, flood-proof project, water and
soil conservation, and utilization of water energy.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang Improving Major Port
</P>
<P>
An international trade building funded by a Hong Kong group
went under construction Thursday in Kashi City, Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The new building, with an investment of 840 million yuan (101
million U.S. dollars), lies in the city's commercial center and is
just a kilometer away from the Kashi Railway Station.
</P>
<P>
Scheduled for completion next May, the building is expected to
be the commodity distribution center for middle and western Asia
as well as Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China News Digest: West on the Move (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shaanxi Province in northwest China is to inject another 2.2
billion yuan this year into upgrading its telecommunications
network, a leading telecom operator said on July 22 in Xi'an,
capital of the province.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Shifu, president of Shanxi Telecom, said that his company
will focus its development efforts on increasing fixed-line usage
and building an information expressway based on its fiber-optical
and broadband telecommunications networks.
</P>
<P>
Fixed-line phone users in Shaanxi so far exceed three million
which means one in ten persons in the province owns a fixed-line
phone, according to Zhou.
</P>
<P>
 Helipad to Be Built at Scenic Mount Huashan
</P>
<P>
A 3.1-ha. helicopter airport is to be constructed at the foot
of Mount Huashan, a renowned tourist destination in northwest
China's Shaanxi Province, according to local official sources.
</P>
<P>
Mount Huashan is one of China's five most famous scenic
mountains, known for its steep and perilous peaks.
</P>
<P>
The new helipad is a strategic move by the provincial
government to accelerate the development of local tourism, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
China Launches Massive Gas Pipeline Construction
</P>
<P>
China will start construction of a 703-km-long gas pipeline
extending from southwest China's Sichuan Province to Hubei
Province in central China before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The gas pipeline, expected to be completed by early 2003, is
part of the country's huge project of sending gas from west to
east.  
</P>
</TEXT>
