<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's AGO Finalizes Soeharto's Dossier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesia's Attorney General
Office said it would charge the country's former President
Soeharto with corruption, and is now finalizing the dossier
detailing the charges expected to be filed against him next month,
local leading newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Marzuki Darusman Wednesday said, "Hopefully we
can hand it over today. We are optimistic that the case will be
filed before August 10."
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the AGO announced the former strong man
would be charged with graft, the Indonesian Observer daily
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Another report said that state prosecutors are ready to file
charges against the former president for misusing 1.4 trillion
rupiah (155 million U.S. dollars) of state funds that have gone to
his seven tax-free charity foundations.
</P>
<P>
Darusman said that Soeharto will be tried in his capacity as
the owner of the foundations, thus dismissing previous speculation
that the former ruler would be accused of abusing power to amass
wealth through the foundations.
</P>
<P>
"As the president at that time, Soeharto had the right to issue
decrees and regulations to raise the funds," Darusman was quoted
by the Jakarta Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
On August 2, the AGO is expected to file Soeharto's case with
the South Jakarta District Court, where most of the evidences and
witnesses in the case are situated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Director of Investigation at the AGO Ris Pandapotan
Sihombing said that Soeharto is primarily charged with violating
article 1 (a) of Law No 3./1971 on Corruption Crimes for
deliberately enriching himself at the state's expense. Then, he is
also subject to secondary charges as stipulated in the corruption
law article 1 (b), under which some one may be convicted for
abusing power so as to cause losses to the state.
</P>
<P>
"The crime carries a maximum life sentence and a minimum 20
years of imprisonment, plus a maximum fine of 30 million rupiah (
around four thousand U.S. dollars)," Sihombing said.
</P>
<P>
While the preparation to file the dossier is under way, as many
as 76 witnesses will be presented at the trial out of the 140
witnesses who have been questioned so far.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto himself now has been put under house arrest and was
banned from leaving the country. He has denied any wrongdoing and
said has no single cent of account abroad.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was forced to step down from his office on May 21,1998
following the worst economic and political crisis and chaos in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
