<HEADLINE> Indonesian National Awakening Party Reappoints Matori  as Its Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The congress of Indonesia's
National Awakening Party (PKB) Wednesday night reappointed Matori
Abdul Djalil as chairman of the party for the period 2000-2005.
</P>
<P>
Matori retained his post after President Abdurrahman Wahid was
unanimously elected as chairman of the party's Board of Patrons by
a plenary session of the congress in Surabaya, capital of East
Java, earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the party's organizational rules, the party's chief
patron would have the power to appoint the new party chairman.
</P>
<P>
During his speech on Wednesday night, Wahid unveiled his
support for Matori's chairmanship bid, saying other candidates
were not available.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that he still needs Matori's closest rival Alwi
Shihab to serve as the minister of foreign affairs. The only other
candidate Mustofa Bisri refused to run for the post.
</P>
<P>
"So Matori is the only one. But he should fulfill two
requirements," said Wahid, who flew to Surabaya from Jakarta after
presiding over a Cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
First, Matori, now a deputy chairman of the People's
Consultative Assembly, must not include his supporters in the PKB'
s executive board and secondly, he must differentiate between
personal funds and funds belonging to the party, Wahid said.
</P>
<P>
The PKB was founded on July 23, 1998 by Wahid and others. The
party's establishment was announced at Wahid's residence in
Ciganjur, South Jakarta. At that time, Wahid was chairman of the
Nahdlatul Ulama (NU), the country's largest Muslim organization.
</P>
<P>
Wahid said he wished to see PKB emerge as a modern party which
could solve its internal problems through its own strengths, even
though the party is promoted by NU.
</P>
<P>
"The PKB does not belong to the NU alone. The PKB and the NU
should be separated," Wahid was quoted by national newspapers
Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The six-day PKB congress is scheduled to close in Surabaya on
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
