<HEADLINE> ASEAN's Forum for Political, Security Dialogue Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Association of the Southeast
Nations (ASEAN) opened its annual forum for political and security
dialogue and cooperation in the Asia-Pacific region on Thursday
here, stressing the importance of continued participation of
defense and military officials in the process.
</P>
<P>
Attending the 7th ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) are foreign
ministers from the 10 ASEAN member countries -- Brunei, Cambodia,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam and its ten dialogue partners -- Australia,
Canada, China, the European Union, India, Japan, New Zealand,
Russia, South Korea and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Also taking part in the forum are the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), Papua New Guinea and Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for DPRK to appear at the regional
security forum as it was accepted only recently after the summit
in June between the leaders of DPRK and the Republic of Korea (ROK)
.
</P>
<P>
The ARF, initiated in 1993, serves as an ASEAN organ for Asia-
Pacific regional confidence building, preventive diplomacy and
disaster relief and China became its full dialogue partner in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
