<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canberra Embarrassed on U.S. NMD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States has embarrassed
Australia by announcing the latter's support to the proposed U.S.
National Missile Defense Plan.
</P>
<P>
It was the lead of a report by The Age daily Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
told a U.S. Senate committee Wednesday that while other Western
nations were skeptical about the NMD system, Australia had backed
the initiative.
</P>
<P>
"I was just in Australia. The Australian government said that
if the United States were to go forward, they would be supportive,
" he was quoted.
</P>
<P>
Cohen emphasized at the Senate hearing that the use of allied
radars to detect missiles was critical for the shield to be
workable.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the United States, Canberra prefer a low profile.
Prime Minister John Howard keeps silence up to now, while Foreign
Minister Alexander Downer, in Bangkok now for regional security
talks, reportedly said Wednesday that the U.S. had not yet decided
whether to proceed with the system and, in any event, it would not
impact on the strategic balance involving the missile system of
Russia or China.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Defense Minister John Moore said Wednesday that
Australia had promised to consider a formal proposal from the
United States but had not committed outright support.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, The Age daily revealed that Australia in
fact has begun its cooperation with the United States in testing
both of the NMD and TMD. The Pine Gap electronic spy base in the
center of the continent has been enlarged last year in order to
relay the early warning data. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
