<HEADLINE> Veteran Manning Contacts Utah Jazz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Veteran forward Danny Manning
met with the Utah Jazz on Wednesday after reaching an agreement to
buy out the final year of his contract with the Milwaukee Bucks.
</P>
<P>
Next season, the 34-year-old backup forward would have entered
the final year of a six-year, 38 million US dollars deal
originally negotiated with the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
Agent Mark Bartlestein said Manning will be available to sign
with other teams from August 1, adding that "Danny is a great
player and he's going to be a great contributor for whatever team
he goes to. Certainly, the Jazz are among those possibilities."
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the Bucks will pay Manning $7.833 million - the
guaranteed amount for next season - over several seasons.
</P>
<P>
Manning played in 72 regular-season games for Milwaukee,
averaging 4.6 points and 2.9 rebounds in 16.9 minutes. In a first-
round playoff series against Indiana, he played in only one game.
</P>
<P>
Manning played on the bronze-medal U.S. Olympic team in 1988
when the Los Angeles Clippers made him the top overall pick in the
NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
Despite his surgically repaired knees, the Jazz like Manning's
experience and hope he can help John Stockton and Karl Malone try
to make another playoff run. 
</P>
