<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Patrick Ewing said he wants to
play three more NBA seasons, even if the New York Knicks don't
want him back after his contract expires next June.
</P>
<P>
"I'd probably like to play two more years after next year. If
it's New York, it's New York. If not, it's somewhere else," Ewing
said for the first time over his plans for the future.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, Ewing signed a four-year 60 million US dollars
contract extension with the Knicks and he was still eligible for
another extension. However, general manager Scott Layden refuses
to discuss anything relating to contracts.
</P>
<P>
Ewing has spent his entire 15-year career with the Knicks,
reaching the NBA
finals twice but never having won a championship. His 15.0 scoring
average last season was the lowest of his career.
</P>
<P>
In the last two seasons, many wondered whether the Knicks were
better off with Ewing or without him as his role in the team
became increasingly less important. 
