<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record 361 Italian Athletes For Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Italy will send a record 361 athletes
- 244 men and 117 women - to the Sydney Olympics, the Italian
Olympic committee announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Italian athletes will compete in 24 out of the 28 sports
including taekwondo and the triathlon. The sports off the Italian
list are badminton, hockey, handball and table tennis.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Olympic organizers are expecting a total of about 10,
200 athletes, about the same as in Atlanta four years ago, when
Italy sent 347.
</P>
<P>
The final lists for the team sports have to be finalized by
September 20. The only major absentees seem to be Jury Chechi, the
gymnast whose injury will prevent competing, and probably winning
gold in his fourth Olympics; marathon runner Franca Fiacconi; and
Daniele Scarpa, who won medals in Atlanta, but failed to qualify
for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Athletics will send 400 meters runner Fabrizio Mori, provided
he gets a recent injury behind him, British-born, but Italian-
married long-jumper Fiona May, triple jump Italian record holder
Fabrizio Donato and walking aces such as Giovanni De Benedictis
and Annarita Sidoti.
</P>
<P>
The soccer team, consisting for the most part of Under-21
players who won the European title in that age category a few
weeks ago, are also strong favorites for some kind of medal.
</P>
<P>
In canoeing, Antonio Rossi and long-serving Iosefa Idem are
expected to continue a long Italian tradition, and the rowers are
also flying down under with high medal hopes.
</P>
<P>
In the recent World Cup final in Zurich, Italian teams got into
seven out of eight finals, winning three golds, a silver and
bronze.
</P>
<P>
The team for the cycling road race is expected to field five
top riders, probably including the great returnee, Marco Pantani.
He still has to announce his intentions, but the rather flat
Olympic course is in no way his cup of tea.
</P>
<P>
Italian track cyclists are expected to make their usual haul of
medals and, on her mountain bike, Paola Pezzi will remain a
cynosure for a host of reasons.
</P>
<P>
After an explosion of talent at the European swimming
championships, Italy's swimmers will have to see how they measure
up to the giants from the United States and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Italian sports administrators, whose prestige rests on how many
medals they can bring home, are laying strong hopes in the water-
polo team, and also the champion volleyball players, who have won
all kinds of gold in recent years, but never Olympic gold.
</P>
<P>
The officials will be expecting further good news from other
traditional Italian strongpoints such as fencing and shooting.
</P>
<P>
There is less optimism about gymnastics, tennis and sailing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
