<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa to Appeal FIFA Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The South African Football
Association (SAFA) is to appeal against FIFA's decision to grant
Germany the 2006 World Cup on the grounds that there were
irregularities in the soccer world governing body's voting process.
</P>
<P>
Danny Jordaan, who heads the South Africa bid committee, said
on Wednesday that SAFA would invoke article 59 in the FIFA statute,
which allowed any bidding country the right to call for an
application for arbitration.
</P>
<P>
Jordaan said although SAFA could have taken the case to court,
it had decided to keep the matter within the confines of FIFA as a
token of South Africa's respect for the governing body.
</P>
<P>
Former Oceania president Charles Dempsey, whose abstention from
voting could have cost South Africa the bid to host the 206 World
Cup, was named as a co-defendant in the arbitration process.
</P>
<P>
SAFA has sent its application for arbitration to FIFA's
headquarters in Zurich and will wait for an answer before deciding
what move to take if the application is turned down.
</P>
<P>
Acting SAFA director Irvin Khoza was reluctant to delve into
the merits of the case, stating only that the bid committee's
legal team had discovered a violation of FIFA's and the Oceania
federation's respective statutes.
</P>
<P>
"We are supremely confident that the statute of FIFA has been
compromised," Khoza said.
</P>
<P>
Khoza also stated the difficulties of taking the matter to
civil court, explaining that FIFA acted within the canton of Swiss
law.
</P>
<P>
Media reports also suggested that South Africa could be kicked
out of FIFA if it pursued the matter in the courts of Europe.
</P>
<P>
"It is not the fear of expulsion that led us to take the
arbitration process, but rather to be compliant with the
regulations of FIFA," Jordaan said.
</P>
<P>
"We have a moral and legal obligation to our people, our
supporters and to the African continent to proceed with this
matter," Jordaan added.
</P>
<P>
FIFA is expected to reply to SAFA by August 3, and if the
application is successful, arbitration will proceed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
