<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Announces National Plan for Health Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The British government Thursday
unveiled its national plan for the health service, with a 10-year
package of sweeping reforms and restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Central to the blueprint was a massive increase in staff
numbers, with an extra 20,000 nurses, 7,500 consultants, 2,000 GPs
and 6,750 other National Health Service (NHS) staff.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair told the House of Commons he planned
to reshape the NHS to match patient need - and recreate a health
service envied by the world.
</P>
<P>
The reaction from patients groups, NHS managers, charities and
doctors has been generally favorable. A spokesman for the Patients
' Association said: "There are some very good ideas in this plan
but now these things have really got to happen and the money has
got to be there. "
</P>
<P>
He added: "The proof of the pudding will be in the eating.It's
all very well the Government saying they are going to tie
consultants into the NHS but unless they give them the financial
incentives the consultants will just go abroad."
</P>
<P>
But doctors' leaders have disputed the claimed workforce boost,
saying thousands of the consultants and GPs were already in the
pipeline before the plan was announced. Doctors also signaled that
they would fight plans to overhaul their contracts and restrict
the amount of private work they can do.
</P>
<P>
The 144-page blueprint for the NHS in England was described by
Health Secretary Alan Milburn as "the most fundamental and far-
reaching reform program".
</P>
<P>
Milburn said: "For the first time, the Government has faced up
to the breadth and depth of problems in the NHS and has addressed
them all in turn. From the state of wards to the doctor's contract,
not one issue has been ducked. "
</P>
<P>
But claims that the plan - drawn up in the last four months by
six committees - will deliver a huge boost in staff numbers have
been disputed.
</P>
<P>
The BMA said an extra 1,000 GPs were already expected in the
health service by 2005, so the national plan pledge of an extra 2,
000 included only 1,000 new posts to add to the current 25,000
family doctors. And an extra 4,500 consultants were already
expected, meaning the claim in the plan to employ an additional 7,
500 was in reality only 3,000 more.
</P>
<P>
Shadow Health Secretary Dr Liam Fox said the plan was full of"
half truths". He said: "This was a wonderful opportunity for Tony
Blair to move from political to clinical priorities.Unforgivably,
he has put his own political survival before the survival of
patients."
</P>
<P>
The plan was drawn up by five action groups, headed by health
ministers and comprising 100 health professionals.
</P>
<P>
The reforms are made possible by Chancellor Gordon Brown's
announcement of the single-biggest injection of money into the NHS.
</P>
<P>
The government has called on NHS workers to embrace the reforms,
and create a high quality service.
</P>
<P>
In return, doctors and other NHS staff will be rewarded with, in
some cases, extra pay and better career opportunities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000727.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Minister Condemns Planned Mass Stayaway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Minister of State for
Information and Publicity Jonathan Moyo described the proposed
strike by farmers and a mass stayaway by workers next week as ill
advised and only designed to derail the land redistribution
process.
</P>
<P>
Moyo issued a statement on Friday evening discouraging workers
and the unemployed from taking part in the action which he said
would bring them nothing but "the now familiar false promises"
with the result of worsening their current condition the
government is trying to improve.
</P>
<P>
"The decision by some white commercial farmers to mobilize
sections of the business community and the political wing of the
trade union movement to go on strike against the land reform
program is most unfortunate," he said.
</P>
<P>
The farmers and the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions will
begin strikes on Monday and Wednesday respectively to protest the
government and police inaction on war veterans occupying about 1,
500 white-owned farms where they are harassing farmers.
</P>
<P>
"The commitment of the government and people of Zimbabwe to an
orderly, transparent and legally defined land reform program is
irreversible," Moyo said.
</P>
<P>
He said the fast tracked resettlement of black peasants on 804
compulsorily acquired farms is being done in an open, transparent,
constitutional, legal and administrative manner whose
implementation is known to the white commercial farmers.
</P>
<P>
According to Moyo, a joint committee of farmers and war
veterans, with an open communication line to President Robert
Mugabe, has provided a useful platform for dialogue which is now
being shunned in favor of anarchy and economic deterioration.
</P>
<P>
"Through this committee some isolated incidents of
misunderstanding between war veterans and farmers have been
reported and the government has expeditiously responded through
the police who have also put in place adequate security
arrangements wherever need has been demonstrated," Moyo said.
</P>
<P>
He said the parliamentary elections are over, and the farmers
are expected to help the government come up with policies which
can turn the economy round to improve people's lives.
</P>
<P>
"The stayaway can only be a distraction," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
