<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's War Veterans Disobeying Ruling Party Instructions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Zimbabwe African
National Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) Friday said former
liberation war veterans are disobeying party instructions to move
out of white-owned farms occupied since February this year.
</P>
<P>
The war veterans, as members of Zanu-pf, should be loyal to its
leadership and carry out its instructions to leave, the Zimbabwe
News Agency quoted Zanu-pf spokesman Nathan Shamuyarira as saying
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We respect Chenjerai Hunzvi as their chairman (in the 50,000-
member Zimbabwe National Liberation War Veterans Association), but
he should lead from the front, not at the back," Shamuyarira said.
</P>
<P>
He urged Hunzvi to "crack down" on his followers who are
refusing to vacate the farms.
</P>
<P>
Shamuyarira was commenting on the current chaotic situation on
some of more than 1,500 farms owned by 4,500 white commercial
farmers. Some of these farmers have begun a countrywide strike in
protest to continued harassment by the former freedom fighters.
</P>
<P>
The former fighters, whose leadership vowed to continue the
occupations, have now resorted to beating up farmers and their
workers, demanding money, evicting owners or just disrupting
production.
</P>
<P>
There are fears that if the farmer strike goes ahead, there
could be a crippling shortage of fresh foods in the country and
preparations for the next season will be jeopardized -- so will
the economy as agriculture is its mainstay.
</P>
<P>
"Hunzvi should now crack down on elements of the war veterans
not obeying instructions. We expect him to lead his members out of
the farms to new settlements. We really emphasize that because the
next two to three weeks are very crucial in our quest for economic
stability," Shamuyarira said.
</P>
<P>
The white farmers, who have sued the government and the police,
have now called for a countrywide strike on Monday which might be
joined by a civil mass action being planned by the Zimbabwe
Congress of Trade Unions and employers also protesting lack of
police protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
