<HEADLINE> S. Leone Backs U.S. Proposed Tribunal for Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Sierra Leone Government Friday
voiced its support for a move propelled by the United States to
set up a special court to try some of the country's rebel leaders.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Freetown quoted Sierra Leone's
Information Minister Julius Spencer as saying that the U.S.-
sponsored draft resolution is in line with requests by them for a
process that has an international dimension.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal should be restricted to dealing with rebel leaders
including Foday Sankoh, the detained head of the Revolutionary
United Front, who must be held accountable for the rebels'
atrocities against civilians, Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have been accused of using a deliberate policy of
terror such as cutting off people's limbs to gain advantage during
the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Richard Holbrooke, U. S. Ambassador to the United Nations, said
earlier that the U.N. Security Council members generally endorsed
the draft resolution proposed by the United States and he hoped a
vote on it would be taken next week.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution suggests that an independent special court
will operate under both Sierra Leone domestic law and
international humanitarian law, and the hearings will be heard
either in Freetown or in one of Sierra Leone's neighboring
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
