<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's War Veterans to Continue Stands Allocation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Leader of Zimbabwe's war veterans
Friday said the war veterans are aware that it is illegal for them
to allocate residential stands on farms near cities, but they will
not stop.
</P>
<P>
Chenjerai Hunzvi told the Zimbabwe News Agency that the
allocation of the residential stands by the war veterans was meant
to put pressure on city authorities to acquire the farms for
residential purposes.
</P>
<P>
The action would legalize the acquisition of farms through
forcing the city authorities to negotiate with the farm owners, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"There is need to put pressure on the city authorities to start
acquiring the farms," he said. "We want to force them to legalize
the acquisition."
</P>
<P>
The war veterans are allocating stands on farms around Harare
to the public and have threatened to sub-divide all the farms they
have occupied since February this year.
</P>
<P>
Kembo Mohadi, Deputy Minister of the Local Government, Public
Works and National Housing, said on Thursday that only city
authorities are empowered by the Urban Councils Act to allocate
stands.
</P>
<P>
City planners have condemned the allocation of the stands which
are done without the necessary infrastructure in place to avoid
outbreak of diseases and environment degradation.
</P>
<P>
According to Harare city authorities, they are not happy with
the developments taking place on the farms, but they have no power
to stop the war veterans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
