<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Trade Unions to Go on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The General Council of the Zimbabwe
Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) Friday decided to stage a three-
day mass stayaway from Wednesday next week.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU Spokesperson Nicholas Mudzengerere told the Zimbabwe News
Agency after a council emergency meeting that the mass stayaway
was meant to press the government to enforce law and order in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The stayaway will come two days after the first ever strike by
Zimbabwean white commercial farmers next Monday in protest to
police inaction on harassment perpetrated by war veterans on some
of the 4,500 white farmers whose land they have been occupying
since February this year.
</P>
<P>
It could also coincide with a general strike by 8,500 Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation workers whose salaries due on
Thursday are only expected to come on August 7.
</P>
<P>
"We are protesting against the continued inaction of the powers
that should instruct the police to do what we all pay them for,"
said Mudzengerere.
</P>
<P>
He said workers in towns and on the farms are being subjected
to violence and beatings which are not justified.
</P>
<P>
Flyers are being distributed in the city center calling on all
workers to support the call for law and order by closing down
businesses and by not going to work and asking colleagues and
acquaintances to do likewise.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU has in the past successfully staged nationwide work
stoppages and critics of the government said another one would
cripple the country's tottering economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has instructed provincial governors
to persuade farmers to call off their strike and give dialogue a
chance while the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic
Front has described the move as ill-advised.
</P>
<P>
But the farmers, who have sued the government for not forcing
the war veterans off their land, said previous efforts to talk to
the government did not bear any fruits. 
</P>
