<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
United Nations Kofi Annan was proceeding to deploy 10 liaison
officers to Addis Ababa and Asmara to facilitate the earliest
implementation of the ceasefire agreement signed by Ethiopia and
Eritrea following the recent U.N. reconnaissance mission to the
two countries, a newspaper quoted the office of the U.N. resident
coordinator as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of the U.N. peacekeeping military liaison
officers arrived here early this week.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of African Unity will also involve in the
deployment, the office said, adding Colonel Jukka Pollanen, head
of the U.N. peacekeeping military liaison officers in Addis Ababa
and his counterpart in Asmara, Eritrea, have kicked off their work
this week.
</P>
<P>
A U.N.-designated officer said here on July 12 that the
deployment of U.N. peacekeeping forces is hopefully completed
before the end of the current rainy season which normally ends
before October.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea, fighting to each other over border
disputes since May 1998, signed the Cessation of Hostilities
Agreement in Algiers, Algeria on June 18, thus having made the
deployment of U.N. peacekeeping forces along the border the two
countries possible. 
</P>
