<HEADLINE> Ugandan, Rwandan Army Officers Meet to Iron out Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Officers from the Uganda People's
Defense Forces (UPDF) and the Rwanda Patriotic Army (RPA) have met
in Kisoro, a city bordering the Democratic Republic of the Congo (
DRC) and Rwanda, to iron out their differences, the New Vision
daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We held a meeting with the RPA commanders to find ways to
ironing out our differences and find ways of defeating (our common)
enemy rather than clashing," Fred Tolit, UPDF's second division
commander, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting held on Wednesday, the two armies agreed to
share information on their operations against the Interahamwe
militias and the Allied Democratic Forces, two rebel groups based
in eastern DRC fighting against the Rwandan and Ugandan armed
forces respectively, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"We believe Rwanda and Uganda are different countries. There
could be differences but this should not drag us to forget our
common security concerns," Tolit said.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed to hold meetings once every two months and they
should rotate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda have their troops stationed in the DRC to
back rival rebel factions fighting against President Laurent
Kabila. The two armies had run into conflicts three times since
June this year in Kisangani of the DRC, which caused heavy
civilian casualties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
