<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Relief food from the World Food
Program (WFP) has been delivered to famine-stricken areas in the
northeastern region of Uganda, the New Vision daily reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The food has been airlifted or ferried by trucks to Kakingol
and Tapac parishes, the worst-hit areas by the drought which are
located on the Mount Moroto slopes, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Speciosa Wandira Kazibwe and Minister of
Disaster Preparedness Tom Butime made an impromptu visit to assess
the famine situation in Moroto and Kotido districts on Wednesday
following press reports that 115 Ugandans died of starvation in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, severe famine has also struck the war-affected
Bundibugyo district bordering the Democratic Republic of the Congo,
leaving most displaced people without sufficient food supplies.
</P>
<P>
The insurgency caused by the rebels of the Allied Democratic
Forces and the long dry spells were to blame for the famine, said
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Some 30 out of 45 districts in Uganda have reportedly been
affected by drought. 
</P>
