<HEADLINE> Refugees in Tanzania Face Worse Nutrition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The health condition of
refugees in Tanzania is likely to deteriorate as the amount of
food currently being supplied to them is below nutritional
requirement, a U.N. official has said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian newspapers Thursday quoted the World Food Program (
WFP) Country Director Irene Lacy as saying that each of the 455,
000 refugees in camps in western Tanzania receives 360 grams of
food, instead of 600 grams needed per day.
</P>
<P>
Expressing her concern over the future health condition of the
refugees who are currently under-fed, Lacy said this would
certainly affect the nutrition status of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the WFP here last week, the
U.N. organization has decided to reduce the food rations to
refugees in Tanzania by 40 percent due to the lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
The huge reduction in the food ration was partly aimed at
ensuring that the available food stocks last longer, Lacy
explained.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) said Wednesday there is little it can do to help
the slash on food rations to refugees in Tanzanian camps.
</P>
<P>
"It is a severe reduction. On its nutritional side, it takes
several months to feel the effect," said the UNHCR Deputy Country
Representative Kai Nelson.
</P>
<P>
The refugee official said they are afraid that refugees might
start leaving their camps in search for food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
