<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Million Kenyan Kids in Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- More than 4 million Kenyan
children are in child labor, making the country the sixth in
prevalence of the practice in Africa, the East African Standard
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Labor Minister Joseph Ngutu on Thursday told a workshop
on child labor that the problem was caused by rising levels of
poverty, population explosion and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the cost-sharing system in primary schools
15 years ago had seen enrollment of children drop from 95 percent
to 75 percent, compounding the problem of child labor.
</P>
<P>
Ngutu noted that current laws relating to labor child were only
remedial rather than preventive and were inadequately enforced.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that it was inevitable that children assisted
in farms at certain times, but it was wrong to use them as
substitutes to paid labor.
</P>
<P>
"When a child is kept from school and made to perform heavy
manual work it becomes totally unacceptable," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ngutu revealed that a policy document addressing all forms of
intolerable child labor has been developed and is awaiting the
cabinet's approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
