<HEADLINE> Italian FM Urges to Boost Ties With Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Sudan's efforts to fight terrorism
and improve human rights conditions will help to favor stronger
economic ties with Italy, Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini told his
Sudanese counterpart Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dini made the statement during a meeting with Sudan's Foreign
Minister Mustafa' Oman Ismail and Rino Serri, the Italian Foreign
undersecretary who is also the special European Union envoy to the
Horn of Africa nations.
</P>
<P>
According to a communique issued after the meeting, the
Sudanese representative outlined initiatives taken by his
government to promote peace, institutional reform, steps towards
democracy and the improvement of Sudan's relations with
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Dini urged Mustafa to take urgent steps in those directions,
with an eye to ending Sudan's 15-year-long civil conflict, which
has devastated the south of the country and raised humanitarian
concerns.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that in the search for a solution to the conflict,
Italy actively supports mediation in its role as chair of the
Joint Partners Forum of IGAD, the Intergovernmental Authority for
Development, which counts Djibouti, Ethiopia, Eritrea, Kenya,
Sudan and Uganda among its members.
</P>
<P>
Dini added that stabilizing the situation would lead to an
intensification of bilateral economic relations as well as a
revival of regional integration within IGAD.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Partners Forum is scheduled to hold its next meeting
in Rome, possibly by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Dini said he was satisfied with dialogue between the European
Union and Khartoum on boosting collaboration on development, which
is conditional on the latter's moves towards democracy.
</P>
<P>
He also praised Sudan for playing a positive role in
encouraging a cease-fire last month between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
