<HEADLINE> Annan Voices Concern at Human Rights Situation in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Thursday voiced his deep concern at the situation of
human rights in Colombia, and particularly at the high incidence
of kidnappings and massacres of civilians.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by his spokesman noted that Annan's support
for the international consensus expressed during the last session
of the United Nations Commission on Human Rights, which called on
the parties to reach a comprehensive human rights and humanitarian
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The statement was released following the U.N. chief's meeting
this afternoon with members of the Colombian Senate's Human Rights
Commission, including its former president Piedad Cordoba.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Ms. Cordoba was kidnapped in Colombia by
paramilitary, but released after a two-week captivity. She was
however forced to move to Canada following continued threats
against her life and her family. 
</P>
</TEXT>
