<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks ended mixed
Thursday with the blue chips rising modestly while the technology
shares falling sharply.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 69.65 at 10,586.13.
The blue chip index bounced back from the fall of 183.49 points
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 145.49 at 3,
842.23, extending its losses of 41.85 points in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor
's 500 index fell 2.80 at 1,449.62.
</P>
<P>
The Dow index rose as the Labor Department reported that the
employment costs remain under control. The report said wages and
benefits rose 1 percent in the second quarter, lower than 1.4
percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The employment costs report could prompt the Federal Reserve to
leave interest rates unchanged in the year. The Federal Reserve
has raised rates six times since June, last year in an effort to
cool off the U.S. economy and keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
Investors rushed into the rate-sensitive retail and financial
sectors and led the Dow's advance.
</P>
<P>
But the report did not encourage investors to move into
technology sector. Investors in the tech sector were pessimistic
about prospects of Internet companies after the online retailer
Amazon.com reported losses of 317 million U.S. dollars in the
second quarter later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The technology stocks were also hit by the disappointing
earning forecasts from the mobile phone maker Nokia. The Finnish
company warned that its third-quarter earnings will likely fall
from the second-quarter levels due to the timing of new product
introduction.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 2.39 at 647.20. But the American Stock
Exchange index fell 2.86 at 912.33 and the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 12.20 at 501.61.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,487 down, 1,388 up and 480
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 1.14 billion shares from 1.17 billion
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
