<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Economic Program Given Green Light By Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government's three-year
economic and financial blueprint, the DPEF, was given the green
light Thursday by both the Lower House and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
In presenting the DPEF, Italian Treasury Minister Vincenzo
Visco delivered an extremely upbeat verdict on the Italian economy,
saying that "the economic situation in Italy is excellent at the
moment and appears to be improving day by day."
</P>
<P>
"The DPEF marks the end of a stage of highly energetic
consolidation, which was very risky and strenuous, but crowned
with un-hoped for success, at least in the eyes of many observers,
" Visco said.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that, by the end of the year, the Italian economy
would enjoy a boom unseen for years, which would "enable the
acceleration of the process of modernization" of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the DPEF, the crucial ratio of the public deficit
to GDP is expected to fall to 1.3 percent this year, rather than
the originally forecast 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The DPEF also sees public debt dropping from 112.1 percent of
GDP at the end of this year to 106.6 percent in 2001 and 99.7
percent at the end of 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
